ado pela morte de Freitas do Amaral |url=https://www.cmjornal.pt/portugal/detalhe/conselho-de-ministros-decreta-luto-nacional-no-sabado-pela-morte-de-freitas-do-amaral |website=cmjornal.pt |language=pt}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Burkina Faso}}\n| 2019\n| 2\n| Victims of the [[Arbinda attack]]\n| <ref>[https://www.dw.com/en/burkina-faso-tense-in-mourning-amid-jihadist-attacks/a-51795594 Burkina Faso tense, in mourning, amid jihadist attacks]</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Albania}}\n| rowspan=2|2019\n| rowspan=2|1\n| rowspan=2|Victims of the [[2019 Albania earthquake]]\n| <ref name=\"AlbaniaQuake2019\">{{cite web|title=The Latest: UN sends disaster assessment experts to Albania|url=https://apnews.com/2dc7f7ae11c24c888813c3b36f14a0f5|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Kosovo}}\n| Kosovo has an ethnic Albanian majority population.<ref name=AlbaniaQuake2019/>\n|-\n| {{flag|Kazakhstan}}\n| 2019\n| 1\n| Victims of [[Bek Air Flight 2100]]\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inform.kz/en/article/3598991|title=President Tokayev declares December 28 a national day of mourning|date=December 27, 2019|website=www.inform.kz}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Iraq}}\n| 2019/20\n| 3\n| Those killed in the [[2019 United States bombing of Kata'ib Hizbollah|U.S. airstrikes against Kata'ib Hezbollah]]\n| Mourning period began on New Year's Eve.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arabic.rt.com/middle_east/1072845-%D8%A5%D8%B9%D9%84%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%82-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%82%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D8%B5%D9%81-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%B1%D9%83%D9%8A/|title=\u0625\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u062f\u0627\u062f \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642 3 \u0623\u064a\u0627\u0645 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0642\u062a\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0635\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0631\u064a\u0643\u064a|website=RT Arabic}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==2020s==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"  style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n! Country\n! Year\n! Days of mourning\n! Reason\n! Notes\n|-\n| {{flag|Iran}}\n| rowspan=2| 2020\n| rowspan=2| 3\n| rowspan=2| Death of [[Qasem Soleimani]], commander of Iran's [[Quds Force]], in a [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|U.S. airstrike]] in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]]\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/news/article/Iraq-At-least-3-Katyusha-rockets-fired-at-14945882.php|title=US kills Iran's most powerful general in Baghdad airstrike|date=January 3, 2020|website=SFChronicle.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Iraq}}\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/middle-east/iraq-mourning-declared-for-soleimani-al-muhandis/1692521|title=Iraq: Mourning declared for Soleimani, al-Muhandis|website=www.aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Iran}}\n| 2020\n| 1\n| Victims of the stampede at [[Funerals of Qasem Soleimani|Qasem Soleimani's funeral]] and the crash of [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]]\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arabic.sputniknews.com/world/202001081043988392-%D8%A5%D9%8A%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%AA%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%86-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%89-%D9%82%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%89-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D8%AF%D8%A7%D9%81%D8%B9-%D9%88%D8%AA%D8%AD%D8%B7%D9%85-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B7%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1%D8%A9/|title=\u0625\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u062a\u0639\u0644\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u062f\u0627\u062f \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0642\u062a\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u062f\u0627\u0641\u0639 \u0648\u062a\u062d\u0637\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0627\u0626\u0631\u0629|website=arabic.sputniknews.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Ukraine}}\n| 2020\n| 1\n| Victims of the crash of [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]]\n| <ref>[https://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/volodimir-zelenskij-ogolosiv-9-sichnya-dnem-zhalobi-v-ukrayi-59177 Volodymyr Zelenskyy declared January 9 the day of mourning in Ukraine due to the UIA plane crash in Iran]</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Oman}}\n| rowspan=6|2020\n| rowspan=6|3\n| rowspan=6|Death of Oman's Sultan [[Qaboos bin Said Al Said]]\n| <ref>[https://twitter.com/OmanNewsAgency/status/1215786603802714113 \u0648\u0625\u0630 \u064a\u0639\u0644\u0646\u064f \u062f\u064a\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0644\u0627\u0637 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0637\u0627\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u062f\u0627\u062f \u0648\u062a\u0639\u0637\u064a\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0645\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0633\u0645\u064a \u0644\u0644\u0642\u0637\u0627\u0639\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0645 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0627\u0635 \u0644\u0645\u062f\u0629 \u062b\u0644\u0627\u062b\u0629 \u0623\u064a\u0627\u0645 \u0648\u062a\u0646\u0643\u064a\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u064a\u0627\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0631\u0628\u0639\u064a\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u062f\u0645\u0629], Oman News Agency</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Kuwait}}\n| <ref>[http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-01/12/c_138697371.htm Kuwaiti emir orders 3 days of mourning over death of Sultan Qaboos]</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Qatar}}\n| <ref>[https://timesofoman.com/article/2546764/Oman/Government/Qatar-declares-three-days-of-mourning-for-HM-Sultan-Qaboos Qatar declares three days of mourning for HM Sultan Qaboos], The Times of Oman</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|UAE}}\n| <ref>[https://gulfnews.com/uae/uae-leaders-mourn-death-of-sultan-qaboos-3-days-of-mourning-declared-1.1578729626522 UAE leaders mourn death of Sultan Qaboos, 3 days of mourning declared]</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Bahrain}}\n| <ref>[https://www.bna.bh/en/news?cms=q8FmFJgiscL2fwIzON1%2BDoCu6CI24pCqdL1RNAFVb1U%3D HM King mourns Sultan Qaboos bin Said] </ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Egypt}}\n| <ref>[https://egyptindependent.com/egypt-announces-3-day-mourning-for-death-of-sultan-qaboos/ Egypt announces 3-day mourning for death of Sultan Qaboos] </ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Niger}}\n| 2020\n| 3\n| Soldiers killed in the [[Battle of Chinagodrar]]\n| <ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/13/africa/niger-military-base-soldiers-dead/index.html Niger declares three days of mourning after 89 soldiers killed in attack on military base], CNN, January 13, 2020</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Czech Republic}}\n| 2020\n| 1\n| Death of Chairman of the Senate of the Czech Republic [[Jaroslav Kubera]]\n| <ref>[https://www.idnes.cz/zpravy/domaci/kubera-statni-smutek.A200127_102209_domaci_kop P\u0159\u00ed\u0161t\u00ed pond\u011bl\u00ed bude v \u010cesku st\u00e1tn\u00ed smutek k uct\u011bn\u00ed pam\u00e1tky sen\u00e1tora Kubery]</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Kenya}}\n| 2020\n| 9\n| Death of the former President of Kenya [[Daniel arap Moi]]\n| <ref>[https://www.scribd.com/document/445467076/PRESIDENTIAL-PROCLAMATION-With-Respect-To-THE-DEATH-OF-H-E-DANIEL-TOROITICH-arap-MOI-C-G-H PRESIDENTIAL PROCLAMATION - With Respect To - THE DEATH OF H.E. DANIEL TOROITICH arap MOI, C.G.H.]</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Egypt}}\n| 2020\n| 3\n| Death of former president of Egipt [[Hosni Mubarak]]\n| <ref>[https://www.egyptindependent.com/egyptian-presidency-announces-three-days-of-national-mourning-following-mubaraks-death/ Egyptian Presidency announces three days of national mourning following Mubarak\u2019s death]</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|Italy}}\n| rowspan=2|2020\n| rowspan=2|1\n| rowspan=2|Martyrs who died in the fight against the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|novel coronavirus disease (COVID-19) outbreak]] and compatriots who died of the disease\n| <ref>[https://www.positanonews.it/2020/03/ravello-giornata-lutto-nazionale-martedi-31-marzo-2020-ore-12/3375250/ Ravello. Giornata di lutto nazionale marted\u00ec 31 marzo 2020, ore 12]</ref>\n|-\n| {{flag|China}}\n| <ref>[https://news.cgtn.com/news/2020-04-03/China-to-mourn-COVID-19-victims-on-April-4-PnBkfHYb2E/index.html China to mourn COVID-19 martyrs, victims nationwide on April 4]</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[European Day of Mourning]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Death customs]]\n[[Category:National days]]\n", "name_user": "Wiktorantkowiak25", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2010s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_day_of_mourning"}
{"title_page": "Ignasi Guardans", "text_new": "{{Catalan name|Guardans|Camb\u00f3}}\n{{External links|date=August 2019}}\n{{Lead too long|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image = IgnasiG08 04.jpg\n\n|office1 = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n|constituency1 = [[Spain (European Parliament constituency)|Spain]]\n|term_start1  = 2004\n|term_end1    = 2009\n\n|office2=[[Member of the Congress of Deputies]]\n|term_start2=1996\n|term_end2=2004\n|constituency2 = [[Barcelona (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Barcelona]]\n\n|office3=[[Parliament of Catalonia|Member of the Parliament of Catalonia]]\n|term_start3=1995\n|term_end3=1996\n|constituency3 = [[Barcelona (Parliament of Catalonia constituency)|Barcelona]]\n\n|birth_name   = Ignasi Guardans i Camb\u00f3\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1964|05|18|df=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]], [[Spain]]\n|nationality  = Spanish \n|party        = [[Democratic Convergence of Catalonia]] (until 2010)\n|children     = \n|alma_mater   = [[University of Navarre]]\n\n|parents=Ramon Guardans i Vall\u00e8s<br />Helena Camb\u00f3 i Mallol\n}}\n\n'''Ignasi Guardans i Camb\u00f3''' ({{IPA-ca|i\u014b\u02c8nazi \u0263w\u0259\u027e\u02c8\u00f0ans i k\u0259m\u02c8bo}}; born on 18 May 1964 in [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]]) is a [[Spain|Spanish]] former [[politician]], currently an independent figure still present in the Spanish media and public opinion. He is one of the 14 grandsons of [[Francesc Camb\u00f3]].\n\nHe started his professional career in the academic and legal research at the [http://www.unav.es/english/ University of Navarra], specialising in Private International Law. In 1992 he moved back to Barcelona and started teaching at its then main Law School ([http://www.ub.edu/dret/ Facultat de Dret, Universitat de Barcelona]). A few years later he joined a law firm as senior associate lawyer, and for some years he mixed his legal practice with the first steps in a political career. In 1995 he was elected to the [http://www.parlament.cat/web Catalan Parliament]. But after a few months, in March 2004 he run as candidate for the Spanish Parliament, or [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso%20Congreso%20de%20los%20Diputados Congreso delos Diputados], where he would seat for two consecutive terms, 1996-2000<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/Diputados/BusqForm?_piref73_1333155_73_1333154_1333154.next_page=/wc/fichaDiputado?idDiputado=278&idLegislatura=6|title=Ignasi Guardans Camb\u00f3; Congreso de los Diputados; VI Legislatura}}</ref> and 2000-2004<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/Diputados/BusqForm?_piref73_1333155_73_1333154_1333154.next_page=/wc/fichaDiputado?idDiputado=140&idLegislatura=7|title=Ignasi Guardans Camb\u00f3; Congreso de los Diputados; VII Legsilatura}}</ref>. He assumed different responsibilities, mostly in the areas of Foreign Affairs, Culture, and Justice & Legal Affairs. During the same period he joined the [http://assembly.coe.int/defaultE.asp Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe] and its Committee for Legal Affairs and Human Rights. His tasks included the screening of candidates to Judges of the [[European Court of Human Rights]].  In 2004 he ran as candidate for the European Parliament, heading a joined candidacy of the main parties from Catalonia, the Basque Country and Galicia called [[:fr:Galeusca|GALEUSCA]].\nAs a Member of the European Parliament he joined the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe ([http://www.alde.eu/ ALDE]), and he assumed [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/28411/Ignasi_GUARDANS%20CAMB%D3.html;jsessionid=3D1D26CB56439ED285A3543238AEB824.node1 different activities and responsibilities]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL1F1E9D2BE0882E0B|title=Ignasi Guardans, European Parliament 2004-2009, v\u00eddeos}}</ref> in particular in the areas of Culture and Media ([[European Parliament Committee on Culture and Education|CULT]]), Justice & Home Affairs ([[European Parliament Committee on Civil Liberties, Justice and Home Affairs|LIBE]]), and International Trade ([[European Parliament Committee on International Trade|INTA]]), where he was the Committee's Vice Chair. He was an active member of the [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/intcoop/tld/default_en.htm Transatlantic Legislators Dialogue] as well of the Delegation for the South Eastern Balkans. He took part as Observer in several international Elections\u2019 Observation missions, including Russia, Palestine<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/26/international/middleeast/disquiet-in-europe-over-hamas-victory.html|title=Disquiet in Europe Over Hamas Victory|last=Cowell|first=Alan|date=January 26, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>, Serbia & Montenegro, and East Timor. Anecdotically, Ignasi Guardans was in [[Mumbai]] during the [[2008 Mumbai attacks|26 November 2008 Mumbai terror attacks]], as the Head of a 36 strong European Parliament Delegation. He was [http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20081127/ignasi-guardans-desde-bombay-librado-por-seis-minutos-ser-uno-los-rehenes/199334.shtml not injured].\n\nIn 2009, following a strong disagreement with the leadership of his party on the status of Catalonia within Spain, and [http://www.vozbcn.com/2009/01/13/6086/guardans-mas-votaria-independencia/ rejecting to assume Catalonia's full independence as a political goal], he lost the confidence of his party to be promoted again as candidate to the EP. In a surprising decision, a few weeks before the end of the Parliament's Term, he was designated by the Spanish Government as Director General of Spain\u2019s [http://www.culturaydeporte.gob.es/cultura-mecd/areas-cultura/cine/el-icaa.html Instituto de la Cinematograf\u00eda y de las Artes Audiovisuales] (ICAA), the Spanish Film Agency. This indirectly included other national and international responsibilities, such as the Presidency of the finance company Audiovisual SGR (today [https://creasgr.com/ CREA SGR]); or the active Membership of the [http://www.efads.eu/ EFADs] in Europe, or the Conference of Latin American Film Authorities or [http://caaci-iberoamerica.org/ CAACI] in Latin America. Following discrepancies with the then Minister of Culture, [[\u00c1ngeles Gonz\u00e1lez-Sinde]] his mandate was called to an end in early December 2010<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2010/film/news/guardans-sacked-as-icaa-topper-1118026170/?jwsource=cl|title=Guardans sacked as ICAA topper|last=Hopwell|first=John|date=October 22, 2010|work=Variety|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\nIn 2011 he was appointed the first Director for Public Affairs & Member Relations at the [https://www.ebu.ch/home European Broadcasting Union] (EBU-UER). Among his tasks he was charged with the management of a Solidarity Program in [https://www.ebu.ch/news/2011/the-european-broadcasting-union support of Mediterranean Broadcasters] during the [[Arab Spring]]. Guardans later moved to Brussels as an independent consultant. Between 2014 and 2014 he channeled his consulting activities in European Public Affairs (mostly in the areas of trade and digital regulation and policy) as a Partner of a global law firm, [[K&L Gates|K&L Gates LLP]] in its Brussels Office. Among other tasks, he acted as Director in Europe for the [https://transatlanticbusiness.org/ TransAtlantic Business Council] (TABC), as the European counterpart to his then colleague former Congressman [[Bart Gordon]]. In parallel, through [http://www.culture-media.eu CUMEDIAE], a non-profit organization specialized in advice and project management in the field of media and the creative sector he co-founded, he has been involved in a number of projects and consulting activities for the arts and for culture and development in different areas such as Film Literacy<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://publications.europa.eu/en/publication-detail/-/publication/43f74b70-f099-484a-83d7-95369fd56f26|title=FILMED: Showing films and other audiovisual content in European schools : obstacles and best practices|date=2015-05-29|website=publications.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>, gender equality in the media in the South Mediterranean<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smedwia.eu/en/home/|title=Women in Audiovisual in the Southern Mediterranean - SouthMediWiA|website=SouthMed WiA|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> or the best identification of cultural indicators<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://disce.eu/|title=DISCE - Developing Inclusive & Sustainable Creative Economies|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>. \n\nPolitically, Guardans terminated any party membership in 2010 when he left [[Democratic Convergence of Catalonia|Converg\u00e8ncia Democr\u00e0tica de Catalunya (CDC)]], a party he had joined in 1992, when its leadership still played a constructive role in Spain and in full respect of the [[Constitution of Spain|Spanish Constitution]]. Ignasi Guardans has remained a politically independent figure afterwards, but has attracted some controversy among part of his former political constituency as he opposes the claim for Catalan independence and many of his former political colleagues have moved towards direct opposition to the current Spanish Constitutional order.\n\nIn the media, Guardans has had a regular presence for many years: for 12 years he was a weekly analyst at the radio talkshow [https://archive.is/20130118161346/http://www.cadenaser.com/buscar/ignasi-guardans La Ventana]; for several years he contributed to the public broadcaster morning show [[:es:Los desayunos de TVE|Los desayunos de TVE]]; and since 2017 he comments live on a weekly basis at [https://www.ondacero.es/programas/julia-en-la-onda/audios-podcast/el-gabinete/ El Gabinete] (Onda Cero) and at [[:es:Hora_25_(programa_de_radio)|Hora 25]] (Cadena Ser). He has been a regular Op-Ed contributor to newspapers such as [http://www.lavanguardia.com/ La Vanguardia], [http://elpais.com/ El Pa\u00eds] and [http://www.elperiodico.com/es/ El Peri\u00f3dico de Catalunya].\n\n== Education ==\n* [[Academic degree|Degree]] in [[law]] ([[University of Navarre]])\n* [[Doctorate]] in law. His PhD research (\"tesis doctoral\") was a comparative case law study in the impact of so-called third countries mandatory laws, such as embargoes or other compulsory laws on the validity and enforceabiluty of international trade contracts. It was subsequently published in 1992 under the title \"Contrato internacional y derecho imperativo extranjero\" (Pamplona, Editorial Aranzadi, {{ISBN|9788470167713}})\n\n== Career ==\n\n* 1987-1992: Deputy Director of the European Documentation Centre (Pamplona)\n* 1988-1992: [[Lecturer]] in [[Conflict of laws|private international law]], [[University of Navarre]]\n* 1992-1996: Professor at the [[University of Barcelona]] and Abat Oliba Study Centre)\n* 1993-2004: Practising Lawyer (Barcelona)\n* 1995: Elected Member of the Catalan Regional Parliament [http://www.parlament.cat/activitat/dspcc/09c259.pdf Parliament's Official Journal]\n* 1996-2004: Elected Member of the Spanish Parliament or [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/Diputados/BusqForm?_piref73_1333155_73_1333154_1333154.next_page=/wc/fichaDiputado&idDiputado=140&idLegislatura=7 Congreso delos Diputados] for [[Barcelona (Spanish Congress Electoral District)|Barcelona]]. Spokesman on various committees, including the [[Joint Committee on the European Union]] (1996\u20132004), the [[Committee on Foreign Affairs (EU)|Committee on Foreign Affairs]] (1996\u20132004) and the [[Committee on Education and Culture]] (200-2004)\n* 1996-2004: Member of [http://www.cosac.eu/ COSAC]\n* 1997-2004: Member of the Parliamentary Assembly of the [https://web.archive.org/web/20120915091206/http://assembly.coe.int/ASP/AssemblyList/AL_MemberDetails.asp?MemberID=4300 Council of Europe]\n* 1998-2004: Member of the Assembly of the [http://www.weu.int Western European Union]\n* 2004-2009: Member of the European Parliament\n* 2009-2010: Director General Instituto de la Cinematograf\u00eda y de las Artes Audiovisuales, ICAA, Ministerio de Cultura\n* 2011: Director for Public Affairs and Member Relations, EBU/UER\n* 2012 - ... Independent Consultant\n*2017-2019: co-Director, Trans Atlantic Business Council\n\n== Decorations ==\n* Orden del M\u00e9rito Civil, or [[Order of Civil Merit|Order of the Civil Merit]], Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Spain\n* Chevalier de l'Ordre des [[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]], Ministry of Culture, France. See: [https://web.archive.org/web/20120708222719/http://ambafrance-es.org/france_espagne/spip.php?article5771 \"Les Arts et les Lettres pour Ignasi Guardans, ancien directeur de l\u2019ICAA\"]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<br />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{MEP}}\n*\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guardans Cambo, Ignasi}}\n[[Category:Convergence and Union politicians]]\n[[Category:Catalan politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:University of Navarra alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Barcelona faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of the 6th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 7th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Convergence and Union MEPs]]\n[[Category:MEPs for Spain 2004\u20132009]]\n[[Category:Survivors of the 2008 Mumbai attacks]]\n[[Category:Members of the 5th Parliament of Catalonia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Catalan name|Guardans|Camb\u00f3}}\n{{External links|date=August 2019}}\n{{Lead too long|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image = IgnasiG08 04.jpg\n\n|office1 = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n|constituency1 = [[Spain (European Parliament constituency)|Spain]]\n|term_start1  = 2004\n|term_end1    = 2009\n\n|office2=[[Member of the Congress of Deputies]]\n|term_start2=1996\n|term_end2=2004\n|constituency2 = [[Barcelona (Congress of Deputies constituency)|Barcelona]]\n\n|office3=[[Parliament of Catalonia|Member of the Parliament of Catalonia]]\n|term_start3=1995\n|term_end3=1996\n|constituency3 = [[Barcelona (Parliament of Catalonia constituency)|Barcelona]]\n\n|birth_name   = Ignasi Guardans i Camb\u00f3\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1964|05|18|df=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]], [[Spain]]\n|nationality  = Spanish \n|party        = [[Democratic Convergence of Catalonia]] (until 2010)\n|children     = \n|alma_mater   = [[University of Navarre]]\n\n|parents=Ramon Guardans Vall\u00e8s & Helena Camb\u00f3 Mallol\n}}\n\n'''Ignasi Guardans i Camb\u00f3''' ({{IPA-ca|i\u0261\u02c8nazi \u0263w\u0259\u027e\u02c8\u00f0ans i k\u0259m\u02c8bo}}; born on 18 May 1964 in [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]]) is a [[Spain|Spanish]] former [[politician]], currently an independent figure still present in the Spanish media and public opinion. He is one of the 14 grandsons of [[Francesc Camb\u00f3]].\n\nHe started his professional career in the academic and legal research at the [http://www.unav.es/english/ University of Navarra], specialising in Private International Law. In 1992 he moved back to Barcelona and started teaching at its then main Law School ([http://www.ub.edu/dret/ Facultat de Dret, Universitat de Barcelona]). A few years later he joined a law firm as senior associate lawyer, and for some years he mixed his legal practice with the first steps in a political career. In 1995 he was elected to the [http://www.parlament.cat/web Catalan Parliament]. But after a few months, in March 2004 he run as candidate for the Spanish Parliament, or [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso%20Congreso%20de%20los%20Diputados Congreso delos Diputados], where he would seat for two consecutive terms, 1996-2000<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/Diputados/BusqForm?_piref73_1333155_73_1333154_1333154.next_page=/wc/fichaDiputado?idDiputado=278&idLegislatura=6|title=Ignasi Guardans Camb\u00f3; Congreso de los Diputados; VI Legislatura}}</ref> and 2000-2004<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/Diputados/BusqForm?_piref73_1333155_73_1333154_1333154.next_page=/wc/fichaDiputado?idDiputado=140&idLegislatura=7|title=Ignasi Guardans Camb\u00f3; Congreso de los Diputados; VII Legsilatura}}</ref>. He assumed different responsibilities, mostly in the areas of Foreign Affairs, Culture, and Justice & Legal Affairs. During the same period he joined the [http://assembly.coe.int/defaultE.asp Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe] and its Committee for Legal Affairs and Human Rights. His tasks included the screening of candidates to Judges of the [[European Court of Human Rights]].  In 2004 he ran as candidate for the European Parliament, heading a joined candidacy of the main parties from Catalonia, the Basque Country and Galicia called [[:fr:Galeusca|GALEUSCA]].\nAs a Member of the European Parliament he joined the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe ([http://www.alde.eu/ ALDE]), and he assumed [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/28411/Ignasi_GUARDANS%20CAMB%D3.html;jsessionid=3D1D26CB56439ED285A3543238AEB824.node1 different activities and responsibilities]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL1F1E9D2BE0882E0B|title=Ignasi Guardans, European Parliament 2004-2009, v\u00eddeos}}</ref> in particular in the areas of Culture and Media ([[European Parliament Committee on Culture and Education|CULT]]), Justice & Home Affairs ([[European Parliament Committee on Civil Liberties, Justice and Home Affairs|LIBE]]), and International Trade ([[European Parliament Committee on International Trade|INTA]]), where he was the Committee's Vice Chair. He was an active member of the [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/intcoop/tld/default_en.htm Transatlantic Legislators Dialogue] as well of the Delegation for the South Eastern Balkans. He took part as Observer in several international Elections\u2019 Observation missions, including Russia, Palestine<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/26/international/middleeast/disquiet-in-europe-over-hamas-victory.html|title=Disquiet in Europe Over Hamas Victory|last=Cowell|first=Alan|date=January 26, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref>, Serbia & Montenegro, and East Timor. Anecdotically, Ignasi Guardans was in [[Mumbai]] during the [[2008 Mumbai attacks|26 November 2008 Mumbai terror attacks]], as the Head of a 36 strong European Parliament Delegation. He was [http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20081127/ignasi-guardans-desde-bombay-librado-por-seis-minutos-ser-uno-los-rehenes/199334.shtml not injured].\n\nIn 2009, following a strong disagreement with the leadership of his party on the status of Catalonia within Spain, and [http://www.vozbcn.com/2009/01/13/6086/guardans-mas-votaria-independencia/ rejecting to assume Catalonia's full independence as a political goal], he lost the confidence of his party to be promoted again as candidate to the EP. In a surprising decision, a few weeks before the end of the Parliament's Term, he was designated by the Spanish Government as Director General of Spain\u2019s [http://www.culturaydeporte.gob.es/cultura-mecd/areas-cultura/cine/el-icaa.html Instituto de la Cinematograf\u00eda y de las Artes Audiovisuales] (ICAA), the Spanish Film Agency. This indirectly included other national and international responsibilities, such as the Presidency of the finance company Audiovisual SGR (today [https://creasgr.com/ CREA SGR]); or the active Membership of the [http://www.efads.eu/ EFADs] in Europe, or the Conference of Latin American Film Authorities or [http://caaci-iberoamerica.org/ CAACI] in Latin America. Following discrepancies with the then Minister of Culture, [[\u00c1ngeles Gonz\u00e1lez-Sinde]] his mandate was called to an end in early December 2010<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2010/film/news/guardans-sacked-as-icaa-topper-1118026170/?jwsource=cl|title=Guardans sacked as ICAA topper|last=Hopwell|first=John|date=October 22, 2010|work=Variety|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\nIn 2011 he was appointed the first Director for Public Affairs & Member Relations at the [https://www.ebu.ch/home European Broadcasting Union] (EBU-UER). Among his tasks he was charged with the management of a Solidarity Program in [https://www.ebu.ch/news/2011/the-european-broadcasting-union support of Mediterranean Broadcasters] during the [[Arab Spring]]. Guardans later moved to Brussels as an independent consultant. Between 2014 and 2014 he channeled his consulting activities in European Public Affairs (mostly in the areas of trade and digital regulation and policy) as a Partner of a global law firm, [[K&L Gates|K&L Gates LLP]] in its Brussels Office. Among other tasks, he acted as Director in Europe for the [https://transatlanticbusiness.org/ TransAtlantic Business Council] (TABC), as the European counterpart to his then colleague former Congressman [[Bart Gordon]]. In parallel, through [http://www.culture-media.eu CUMEDIAE], a non-profit organization specialized in advice and project management in the field of media and the creative sector he co-founded, he has been involved in a number of projects and consulting activities for the arts and for culture and development in different areas such as Film Literacy<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://publications.europa.eu/en/publication-detail/-/publication/43f74b70-f099-484a-83d7-95369fd56f26|title=FILMED: Showing films and other audiovisual content in European schools : obstacles and best practices|date=2015-05-29|website=publications.europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>, gender equality in the media in the South Mediterranean<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.smedwia.eu/en/home/|title=Women in Audiovisual in the Southern Mediterranean - SouthMediWiA|website=SouthMed WiA|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> or the best identification of cultural indicators<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://disce.eu/|title=DISCE - Developing Inclusive & Sustainable Creative Economies|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>. \n\nPolitically, Guardans terminated any party membership in 2010 when he left [[Democratic Convergence of Catalonia|Converg\u00e8ncia Democr\u00e0tica de Catalunya (CDC)]], a party he had joined in 1992, when its leadership still played a constructive role in Spain and in full respect of the [[Constitution of Spain|Spanish Constitution]]. Ignasi Guardans has remained a politically independent figure afterwards, but has attracted some controversy among part of his former political constituency as he opposes the claim for Catalan independence and many of his former political colleagues have moved towards direct opposition to the current Spanish Constitutional order.\n\nIn the media, Guardans has had a regular presence for many years: for 12 years he was a weekly analyst at the radio talkshow [https://archive.is/20130118161346/http://www.cadenaser.com/buscar/ignasi-guardans La Ventana]; for several years he contributed to the public broadcaster morning show [[:es:Los desayunos de TVE|Los desayunos de TVE]]; and since 2017 he comments live on a weekly basis at [https://www.ondacero.es/programas/julia-en-la-onda/audios-podcast/el-gabinete/ El Gabinete] (Onda Cero) and at [[:es:Hora_25_(programa_de_radio)|Hora 25]] (Cadena Ser). He has been a regular Op-Ed contributor to newspapers such as [http://www.lavanguardia.com/ La Vanguardia], [http://elpais.com/ El Pa\u00eds] and [http://www.elperiodico.com/es/ El Peri\u00f3dico de Catalunya].\n\n== Education ==\n* [[Academic degree|Degree]] in [[law]] ([[University of Navarre]])\n* [[Doctorate]] in law. His PhD research (\"tesis doctoral\") was a comparative case law study in the impact of so-called third countries mandatory laws, such as embargoes or other compulsory laws on the validity and enforceabiluty of international trade contracts. It was subsequently published in 1992 under the title \"Contrato internacional y derecho imperativo extranjero\" (Pamplona, Editorial Aranzadi, {{ISBN|9788470167713}})\n\n== Career ==\n\n* 1987-1992: Deputy Director of the European Documentation Centre (Pamplona)\n* 1988-1992: [[Lecturer]] in [[Conflict of laws|private international law]], [[University of Navarre]]\n* 1992-1996: Professor at the [[University of Barcelona]] and Abat Oliba Study Centre)\n* 1993-2004: Practising Lawyer (Barcelona)\n* 1995: Elected Member of the Catalan Regional Parliament [http://www.parlament.cat/activitat/dspcc/09c259.pdf Parliament's Official Journal]\n* 1996-2004: Elected Member of the Spanish Parliament or [http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/Diputados/BusqForm?_piref73_1333155_73_1333154_1333154.next_page=/wc/fichaDiputado&idDiputado=140&idLegislatura=7 Congreso delos Diputados] for [[Barcelona (Spanish Congress Electoral District)|Barcelona]]. Spokesman on various committees, including the [[Joint Committee on the European Union]] (1996\u20132004), the [[Committee on Foreign Affairs (EU)|Committee on Foreign Affairs]] (1996\u20132004) and the [[Committee on Education and Culture]] (200-2004)\n* 1996-2004: Member of [http://www.cosac.eu/ COSAC]\n* 1997-2004: Member of the Parliamentary Assembly of the [https://web.archive.org/web/20120915091206/http://assembly.coe.int/ASP/AssemblyList/AL_MemberDetails.asp?MemberID=4300 Council of Europe]\n* 1998-2004: Member of the Assembly of the [http://www.weu.int Western European Union]\n* 2004-2009: Member of the European Parliament\n* 2009-2010: Director General Instituto de la Cinematograf\u00eda y de las Artes Audiovisuales, ICAA, Ministerio de Cultura\n* 2011: Director for Public Affairs and Member Relations, EBU/UER\n* 2012 - ... Independent Consultant\n*2017-2019: co-Director, Trans Atlantic Business Council\n\n== Decorations ==\n* Orden del M\u00e9rito Civil, or [[Order of Civil Merit|Order of the Civil Merit]], Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Spain\n* Chevalier de l'Ordre des [[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]], Ministry of Culture, France. See: [https://web.archive.org/web/20120708222719/http://ambafrance-es.org/france_espagne/spip.php?article5771 \"Les Arts et les Lettres pour Ignasi Guardans, ancien directeur de l\u2019ICAA\"]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<br />\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{MEP}}\n*\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guardans Cambo, Ignasi}}\n[[Category:Convergence and Union politicians]]\n[[Category:Catalan politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:University of Navarra alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Barcelona faculty]]\n[[Category:Members of the 6th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 7th Congress of Deputies (Spain)]]\n[[Category:Convergence and Union MEPs]]\n[[Category:MEPs for Spain 2004\u20132009]]\n[[Category:Survivors of the 2008 Mumbai attacks]]\n[[Category:Members of the 5th Parliament of Catalonia]]\n", "name_user": "Girrit", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:correction pronunciation and parents' names", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ignasi_Guardans"}
{"title_page": "Stephens\u2013Townsend\u2013Murphy Party", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|date=April 2010}}\n\nThe '''Stephens\u2013Townsend\u2013Murphy Party''' consisted of ten families who migrated from [[Iowa]] to [[California]] prior to the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] and the [[California Gold Rush]].  The Stephens Party is significant in California history because they were the first wagon train to cross the [[Sierra Nevada (United States)|Sierra Nevada]] during the expansion of the [[American West]]. In 1844, they pioneered the first route at or near what was later named [[Donner Pass]]. The crossing was a year before [[John Charles Fremont#Third expedition|John C. Fremont]], two years before the [[Donner Party]], and five years before the 1848\u201349 Gold Rush.\n\n==Journey==\nThe 50-member Stephens group left near present-day [[Council Bluffs, Iowa]] on May 22, 1844. They departed with a larger group of [[Oregon]]-bound settlers in a train of 40 wagons. Fifty travelers left Iowa; 52 arrived in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] with the Stephens party, as there were two births along the way. [[Elisha Stephens]] was elected captain of the wagon train because he had spent several years as a [[mountain man]] and [[beaver]] hunter in the [[Pacific Northwest]]. He also had skills as a [[blacksmith]]. He had worked at the [[Potawatomi]] Council Bluffs US Indian Subagency before resigning to go to California.\n\nDr. John Townsend, his wife Elizabeth, and her younger brother Moses Schallenberger, were also going west.  A man of vision, Townsend wanted a chance at grand adventure and opportunity in California. He would become the first licensed [[physician]] in California.\n\nThe largest family group in the party was headed by Martin Murphy, Sr. His family had 23 members. As Irish [[Catholic]]s, the Murphy family, along with the Martin and Sullivan families, were seeking religious, economic, and political freedoms in the West. The group included James Miller (1814\u20131890), an Irishman, who would marry  Martin Murphy, Sr.'s third daughter and settle at Rancho San Pedro, Santa Margarita y Las Gallinas near [[San Rafael, California|San Rafael]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Irish Families on the California Trail: Pioneers and 49ers from the Earliest Days Including the Gold Rush & San Francisco |author=Michael C. O'Laughlin |year=2003 |publisher=Irish Roots Cafe |page=F-26 |isbn=  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vpJWCR_Mv4QC&lpg=SL6-PA26&ots=HAzPfNEjf4&dq=oregon%20%22James%20Miller%22%20irish&pg=SL6-PA26#v=onepage&q=%22James%20Miller%22%20&f=false |accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |title=Murphy, Hill and Miller Were Interesting Marin Pioneers |author= |date=July 19, 1934 |publisher=The San Anselmo Herald |page=4 |location=San Anselmo, California}}</ref>\n\nThe party was guided by [[mountain men]] [[Caleb Greenwood]] and Isaac Hitchcock. In [[Wyoming]], Hitchcock, who had been \"trapping and trading\" in California in 1832, led the party west from the Big Sandy River to the [[Green River (Colorado River)|Green River]] bypassing [[Fort Bridger]]. The [[Emigrant Trail in Wyoming#Sublette-Greenwood Cutoff|cutoff]] was dangerous, as it crossed {{convert|40|mi|km}} without water for livestock, but it cut {{convert|85|mi|km}} and 7 days off the established route. The cutoff was later popularized in a guide book and used heavily by miners heading to the [[California Gold Rush]].\n\nIn the Sierra Nevada they encountered snow and  on November 14, 1844, the party split.  Six of the party, including Elizabeth Townsend, set off on horseback following the [[Truckee River]] southward with the aim of reaching Sutter Fort quickly and sending help back.  They became the first Americans to step foot on the shore of [[Lake Tahoe]] on November 16 ([[John C. Fr\u00e9mont]] had been the first American to see it the previous February). They arrived at Sutters Fort on December 10.<ref name=\"truckee\">{{cite web |title=The First Pioneer Wagons Crossed the Sierra Over 160 Years Ago |url=https://www.truckeehistory.org/the-first-pioneer-wagons-crossed-the-sierra-over-160-years-ago.html |website=Truckee-Donner Historical Society |accessdate=29 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nThe rest of the party continued until reaching Truckey's (or Truckee) Lake (now [[Donner Lake]]).  Here they left six of their eleven wagons because of difficulties getting the wagons over the pass and continued with the remaining five.  At one point they had to unhitch the wagons and haul them up a cliff with makeshift pulleys while the oxen were led up through a narrow slot.  On November 25 they managed to reach the top of the pass.  Three men, Joseph Foster, Allan Montgomery, and Moses Schallenberger, returned to the wagons with the intent of watching over them until the snow melted.  They quickly put up a cabin (later used by the Donner Party) but soon realized that it would be very difficult for them to survive the winter.  On makeshift snowshoes they set out after the party ahead of them but after the first day the youngest, eighteen-year-old Moses Schallenberger realized he couldn't make it and returned to the wagons.  He survived only by trapping [[Sierra Nevada red fox|High Sierra fox]]es for food.<ref name=\"truckee\"/>\n\nThe rest of the party after crossing the pass continued until snow made it impossible to continue with wagons on the upper [[Yuba River]] valley. They set up camp and, on December 6, 17 of the adult men continue in order to find help while the women, children, and two adult men remained in the camp.  Unfortunately most of the men were enticed or coerced to fight with [[John A. Sutter|Captain John Sutter]] for Mexican California Governor [[Manuel Micheltorena]] in exchange for promises of land grants. Instead of joining them, Dennis Martin returned to the upper Yuba with supplies for the women and children. Upon learning of the plight of Moses Schallenberger, twenty-three-year-old Martin crossed the snowbound [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] in mid-winter (February, 1845) to rescue Schallenberger at Donner Lake.<ref name=Regnery>{{cite journal |title=Dennis Martin once owned Stanford's backlands, including SLAC, Jasper Ridge, and Webb Ranch |author=Dorothy Regnery |journal=Stanford Historical Society Newsletter |date=September 1983 |url=http://histsoc.stanford.edu/pdfST/ST7no3.pdf |accessdate=2011-09-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927162417/http://histsoc.stanford.edu/pdfST/ST7no3.pdf |archivedate=2011-09-27 }}</ref> Martin showed Schallenberger how to construct proper snowshoes and successfully the two recrossed the Sierras to the Central Valley.<ref>{{cite book |title=Moses Schallenberger at Truckey's Lake, 1844-1845 |author=Moses Schallenberger |editor=Charles H. Todd |publisher=19th Century Publications |location=Winters, California |year=2007}}</ref>\n\n==Afterwards==\n\nElisha Stephens settled in the [[San Jose, California|San Jose]]/[[Cupertino]] area, where [[Stevens Creek (California)|Stevens Creek]] [sic] is named for him. In 1862, he left the area, heading to [[Kern County, California|Kern County]] in central California. He was the first non-native settler in what is today the city of [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]]. A state historic plaque in that city marks the approximate site of his homestead. Stephens died in Bakersfield in 1887. He was buried in Union Cemetery. His gravesite was discovered in 2009 by members of the [[Kern County]] Genealogical Society. On May 1, 2010 the [[Oregon-California Trails Association]] (OCTA) California/Nevada Chapter in cooperation with the Kern County Historical Society (KCHS) installed a historical plaque at the gravesite of Elisha Stephens.\n\nJohn Townsend was California's first licensed physician.  He and his wife, Elizabeth, treated the victims of the 1850 [[cholera]] epidemic in San Jose until they died of it in December 1850.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kirkpatrick |first1=Jane |title=One More River To Cross |url=https://jkbooks.com/Book%20Pages/OneMoreRiverToCross.html |website=jkbooks.com |accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref>  Elizabeth's younger brother, Moses Schallenberger,  settled in Santa Clara county and died in 1909.  Schallenberger Elementary School in the [[San Jos\u00e9 Unified School District]] and Schallenberger Ridge just south of Donner Lake are named for him<ref>{{cite news |last1=McLaughlin |first1=Mark |title=Moses Schallenberger: Alone at Donner Lake, Part II |url=https://thetahoeweekly.com/2014/11/moses-schallenberger-alone-donner-lake-part-ii/ |accessdate=29 August 2019 |work=Tahoe Weekly |date=19 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Contact and Directions {{!}} School Information {{!}} Who We Are {{!}} Schallenberger Elementary |url=https://schallenberger.sjusd.org/who-we-are/school-information/ |website=schallenberger.sjusd.org |accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1846, Martin Murphy Sr. purchased the ''[[Rancho Ojo del Agua de la Coche]]''. Son Martin Murphy Jr. was the founder of the city of [[Sunnyvale, California|Sunnyvale]]. Sons John and Daniel struck gold in the Sierras, then made a fortune selling dry goods to local miners and Native Americans. The town they established in the Sierra foothills still bears the family name of [[Murphys, California|Murphys]]. Helen Murphy, the youngest daughter of Martin Sr., married [[Charles Maria Weber]], the founder of the city of [[Stockton, California|Stockton]].\n\nDennis Martin also struck gold in the Sierras and purchased ranch properties from the grantees of [[Rancho Ca\u00f1ada de Raymundo]] and [[Rancho Corte de Madera]] which include much of the modern day back lands of [[Stanford University]], including the [[Stanford Linear Accelerator Center]], [[Jasper Ridge Biological Preserve]], the [[Ladera, California|Ladera]] subdivision and the Webb Ranch. After financial misfortune and land disputes typical of the era, his lands were bought by [[Leland Stanford]] in November, 1882. Dennis Martin died in June 1890 and was buried at the St. Dennis Cemetery (Martin had built his own church) on his former property (then Stanford's).<ref name=Regnery /> [[Woodside, California|Woodside's]] [[Dennis Martin Creek]] is named for him.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Elisha_Stephens.jpg|Elisha Stephens\nFile:Stephens (Stevens) Pass Plaque.jpg|\"Stephens Pass\" Plaque at Donner Pass, California.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: Image:CA State Historic Marker 732.jpg|State Historic Marker at the site of the last home of Elisha Stephens, Bakersfield California. -->\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|22em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Pages 100\u2013108, 118, 126, 327\u201328, \"Old Greenwood\", Revised edition, by co-authors Charles Kelly and Dale L. Morgan, The Talisman Press 1965, Georgetown, California.\n* Appendix to \"First And Last Consul\" by author John A. Hawgood, page 113 (re: Isaac Hitchcock in CA in 1832) and page 118 (re: Joseph Walker in CA in 1833).\n* Re: Newly discovered Elisha Stephens' gravesite....Kern Gen Vol 47 No 1 March 2010, published by the Kern County Genealogical Society.\n* [http://www.truckeehistory.org/history23.htm \"The Stephens-Townsend-Murphy Party\"], Truckee-Donner Historical Society, Inc.\n* [http://www.sierrasun.com/article/20060505/LIFE/60505001 \"Emigrants and extinction: Wildlife impacted by settlement\"], ''Sierra Sun''\n* [http://ourtown.sacbee.com/news.wsi?group_id=627&news_id=1 \"Caleb Greenwood\"], ''Sacramento Bee''\n* Rose, James J. ''Sierra Trailblazers: First Pioneer Wagons Over the Sierra Nevada''\n* [http://www.thecaliforniatrail.org/, video ''Forgotten Journey''], California Trail, Forgotten Journey Productions, 2004.\n* [http://www.fs.fed.us/r5/tahoe/documents/big_bend/emigrant_tr.htm \"Finding the Way\"], USDA Forest Service, Tahoe National Forest, Big Bend Visitor Center, 1999\n* [http://wyoshpo.state.wy.us/trailsdemo/sublettegreenwood.htm \"Sublette Greenwood Cutoff\"], ''Wyoming Emigrant Trails'', Wyoming State Historic Preservation Office\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|first=George R|last=Stewart|title=The Opening of the California Trail: The Story of the Stevens Party from the Reminiscences of Moses Schallenberger as Set down for H. H. Bancroft about 1885, Edited and Expanded by Horace S. Foote in 1888}}\n*George R. Stewart, ''The California Trail'', New York: McGraw-Hill, 1962\n\n[[Category:Mexican California]]\n[[Category:History of the Sierra Nevada (U.S.)]]\n[[Category:History of the Great Basin]]\n[[Category:Stephens-Townsend-Murphy Party]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=April 2010}}\n\nThe '''Stephens\u2013Townsend\u2013Murphy Party''' consisted of ten families who migrated from [[Iowa]] to [[California]] prior to the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] and the [[California Gold Rush]].  The Stephens Party is significant in California history because they were the first wagon train to cross the [[Sierra Nevada (United States)|Sierra Nevada]] during the expansion of the [[American West]]. In 1844, they pioneered the first route at or near what was later named [[Donner Pass]]. The crossing was a year before [[John Charles Fremont#Third expedition|John C. Fremont]], two years before the [[Donner Party]] and five years before the 1848\u201349 Gold Rush.\n\n==Journey==\nThe 50-member Stephens group left near present-day [[Council Bluffs, Iowa]] on May 22, 1844. They departed with a larger group of [[Oregon]]-bound settlers in a train of 40 wagons. Fifty travelers left Iowa; 52 arrived in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] with the Stephens party, as there were two births along the way. [[Elisha Stephens]] was elected captain of the wagon train because he had spent several years as a [[mountain man]] and [[beaver]] hunter in the [[Pacific Northwest]]. He also had skills as a [[blacksmith]]. He had worked at the [[Potawatomi]] Council Bluffs US Indian Subagency before resigning to go to California.\n\nDr. John Townsend, his wife Elizabeth, and her younger brother Moses Schallenberger, were also going west.  A man of vision, Townsend wanted a chance at grand adventure and opportunity in California. He would become the first licensed [[physician]] in California.\n\nThe largest family group in the party was headed by Martin Murphy, Sr. His family had 23 members. As Irish [[Catholic]]s, the Murphy family, along with the Martin and Sullivan families, were seeking religious, economic, and political freedoms in the West. The group included James Miller (1814\u20131890), an Irishman, who would marry  Martin Murphy, Sr.'s third daughter and settle at Rancho San Pedro, Santa Margarita y Las Gallinas near [[San Rafael, California|San Rafael]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Irish Families on the California Trail: Pioneers and 49ers from the Earliest Days Including the Gold Rush & San Francisco |author=Michael C. O'Laughlin |year=2003 |publisher=Irish Roots Cafe |page=F-26 |isbn=  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vpJWCR_Mv4QC&lpg=SL6-PA26&ots=HAzPfNEjf4&dq=oregon%20%22James%20Miller%22%20irish&pg=SL6-PA26#v=onepage&q=%22James%20Miller%22%20&f=false |accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |title=Murphy, Hill and Miller Were Interesting Marin Pioneers |author= |date=July 19, 1934 |publisher=The San Anselmo Herald |page=4 |location=San Anselmo, California}}</ref>\n\nThe party was guided by [[mountain men]] [[Caleb Greenwood]] and Isaac Hitchcock. In [[Wyoming]], Hitchcock, who had been \"trapping and trading\" in California in 1832, led the party west from the Big Sandy River to the [[Green River (Colorado River)|Green River]] bypassing [[Fort Bridger]]. The [[Emigrant Trail in Wyoming#Sublette-Greenwood Cutoff|cutoff]] was dangerous, as it crossed {{convert|40|mi|km}} without water for livestock, but it cut {{convert|85|mi|km}} and 7 days off the established route. The cutoff was later popularized in a guide book and used heavily by miners heading to the [[California Gold Rush]].\n\nIn the Sierra Nevada they encountered snow and  on November 14, 1844, the party split.  Six of the party, including Elizabeth Townsend, set off on horseback following the [[Truckee River]] southward with the aim of reaching Sutter Fort quickly and sending help back.  They became the first Americans to step foot on the shore of [[Lake Tahoe]] on November 16 ([[John C. Fr\u00e9mont]] had been the first American to see it the previous February). They arrived at Sutters Fort on December 10.<ref name=\"truckee\">{{cite web |title=The First Pioneer Wagons Crossed the Sierra Over 160 Years Ago |url=https://www.truckeehistory.org/the-first-pioneer-wagons-crossed-the-sierra-over-160-years-ago.html |website=Truckee-Donner Historical Society |accessdate=29 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nThe rest of the party continued until reaching Truckey's (or Truckee) Lake (now [[Donner Lake]]).  Here they left six of their eleven wagons because of difficulties getting the wagons over the pass and continued with the remaining five.  At one point they had to unhitch the wagons and haul them up a cliff with makeshift pulleys while the oxen were led up through a narrow slot.  On November 25 they managed to reach the top of the pass.  Three men, Joseph Foster, Allan Montgomery, and Moses Schallenberger, returned to the wagons with the intent of watching over them until the snow melted.  They quickly put up a cabin (later used by the Donner Party) but soon realized that it would be very difficult for them to survive the winter.  On makeshift snowshoes they set out after the party ahead of them but after the first day the youngest, eighteen-year-old Moses Schallenberger realized he couldn't make it and returned to the wagons.  He survived only by trapping [[Sierra Nevada red fox|High Sierra fox]]es for food.<ref name=\"truckee\"/>\n\nThe rest of the party after crossing the pass continued until snow made it impossible to continue with wagons on the upper [[Yuba River]] valley. They set up camp and, on December 6, 17 of the adult men continue in order to find help while the women, children, and two adult men remained in the camp.  Unfortunately most of the men were enticed or coerced to fight with [[John A. Sutter|Captain John Sutter]] for Mexican California Governor [[Manuel Micheltorena]] in exchange for promises of land grants. Instead of joining them, Dennis Martin returned to the upper Yuba with supplies for the women and children. Upon learning of the plight of Moses Schallenberger, twenty-three-year-old Martin crossed the snowbound [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]] in mid-winter (February, 1845) to rescue Schallenberger at Donner Lake.<ref name=Regnery>{{cite journal |title=Dennis Martin once owned Stanford's backlands, including SLAC, Jasper Ridge, and Webb Ranch |author=Dorothy Regnery |journal=Stanford Historical Society Newsletter |date=September 1983 |url=http://histsoc.stanford.edu/pdfST/ST7no3.pdf |accessdate=2011-09-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927162417/http://histsoc.stanford.edu/pdfST/ST7no3.pdf |archivedate=2011-09-27 }}</ref> Martin showed Schallenberger how to construct proper snowshoes and successfully the two recrossed the Sierras to the Central Valley.<ref>{{cite book |title=Moses Schallenberger at Truckey's Lake, 1844-1845 |author=Moses Schallenberger |editor=Charles H. Todd |publisher=19th Century Publications |location=Winters, California |year=2007}}</ref>\n\n==Afterwards==\n\nElisha Stephens settled in the [[San Jose, California|San Jose]]/[[Cupertino]] area, where [[Stevens Creek (California)|Stevens Creek]] [sic] is named for him. In 1862, he left the area, heading to [[Kern County, California|Kern County]] in central California. He was the first non-native settler in what is today the city of [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]]. A state historic plaque in that city marks the approximate site of his homestead. Stephens died in Bakersfield in 1887. He was buried in Union Cemetery. His gravesite was discovered in 2009 by members of the [[Kern County]] Genealogical Society. On May 1, 2010 the [[Oregon-California Trails Association]] (OCTA) California/Nevada Chapter in cooperation with the Kern County Historical Society (KCHS) installed a historical plaque at the gravesite of Elisha Stephens.\n\nJohn Townsend was California's first licensed physician.  He and his wife, Elizabeth, treated the victims of the 1850 [[cholera]] epidemic in San Jose until they died of it in December 1850.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kirkpatrick |first1=Jane |title=One More River To Cross |url=https://jkbooks.com/Book%20Pages/OneMoreRiverToCross.html |website=jkbooks.com |accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref>  Elizabeth's younger brother, Moses Schallenberger,  settled in Santa Clara county and died in 1909.  Schallenberger Elementary School in the [[San Jos\u00e9 Unified School District]] and Schallenberger Ridge just south of Donner Lake are named for him<ref>{{cite news |last1=McLaughlin |first1=Mark |title=Moses Schallenberger: Alone at Donner Lake, Part II |url=https://thetahoeweekly.com/2014/11/moses-schallenberger-alone-donner-lake-part-ii/ |accessdate=29 August 2019 |work=Tahoe Weekly |date=19 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Contact and Directions {{!}} School Information {{!}} Who We Are {{!}} Schallenberger Elementary |url=https://schallenberger.sjusd.org/who-we-are/school-information/ |website=schallenberger.sjusd.org |accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1846, Martin Murphy Sr. purchased the ''[[Rancho Ojo del Agua de la Coche]]''. Son Martin Murphy Jr. was the founder of the city of [[Sunnyvale, California|Sunnyvale]]. Sons John and Daniel struck gold in the Sierras, then made a fortune selling dry goods to local miners and Native Americans. The town they established in the Sierra foothills still bears the family name of [[Murphys, California|Murphys]]. Helen Murphy, the youngest daughter of Martin Sr., married [[Charles Maria Weber]], the founder of the city of [[Stockton, California|Stockton]].\n\nDennis Martin also struck gold in the Sierras and purchased ranch properties from the grantees of [[Rancho Ca\u00f1ada de Raymundo]] and [[Rancho Corte de Madera]] which include much of the modern day back lands of [[Stanford University]], including the [[Stanford Linear Accelerator Center]], [[Jasper Ridge Biological Preserve]], the [[Ladera, California|Ladera]] subdivision and the Webb Ranch. After financial misfortune and land disputes typical of the era, his lands were bought by [[Leland Stanford]] in November, 1882. Dennis Martin died in June 1890 and was buried at the St. Dennis Cemetery (Martin had built his own church) on his former property (then Stanford's).<ref name=Regnery /> [[Woodside, California|Woodside's]] [[Dennis Martin Creek]] is named for him.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Elisha_Stephens.jpg|Elisha Stephens\nFile:Stephens (Stevens) Pass Plaque.jpg|\"Stephens Pass\" Plaque at Donner Pass, California.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: Image:CA State Historic Marker 732.jpg|State Historic Marker at the site of the last home of Elisha Stephens, Bakersfield California. -->\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|22em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Pages 100\u2013108, 118, 126, 327\u201328, \"Old Greenwood\", Revised edition, by co-authors Charles Kelly and Dale L. Morgan, The Talisman Press 1965, Georgetown, California.\n* Appendix to \"First And Last Consul\" by author John A. Hawgood, page 113 (re: Isaac Hitchcock in CA in 1832) and page 118 (re: Joseph Walker in CA in 1833).\n* Re: Newly discovered Elisha Stephens' gravesite....Kern Gen Vol 47 No 1 March 2010, published by the Kern County Genealogical Society.\n* [http://www.truckeehistory.org/history23.htm \"The Stephens-Townsend-Murphy Party\"], Truckee-Donner Historical Society, Inc.\n* [http://www.sierrasun.com/article/20060505/LIFE/60505001 \"Emigrants and extinction: Wildlife impacted by settlement\"], ''Sierra Sun''\n* [http://ourtown.sacbee.com/news.wsi?group_id=627&news_id=1 \"Caleb Greenwood\"], ''Sacramento Bee''\n* Rose, James J. ''Sierra Trailblazers: First Pioneer Wagons Over the Sierra Nevada''\n* [http://www.thecaliforniatrail.org/, video ''Forgotten Journey''], California Trail, Forgotten Journey Productions, 2004.\n* [http://www.fs.fed.us/r5/tahoe/documents/big_bend/emigrant_tr.htm \"Finding the Way\"], USDA Forest Service, Tahoe National Forest, Big Bend Visitor Center, 1999\n* [http://wyoshpo.state.wy.us/trailsdemo/sublettegreenwood.htm \"Sublette Greenwood Cutoff\"], ''Wyoming Emigrant Trails'', Wyoming State Historic Preservation Office\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|first=George R|last=Stewart|title=The Opening of the California Trail: The Story of the Stevens Party from the Reminiscences of Moses Schallenberger as Set down for H. H. Bancroft about 1885, Edited and Expanded by Horace S. Foote in 1888}}\n*George R. Stewart, ''The California Trail'', New York: McGraw-Hill, 1962\n\n[[Category:Mexican California]]\n[[Category:History of the Sierra Nevada (U.S.)]]\n[[Category:History of the Great Basin]]\n[[Category:Stephens-Townsend-Murphy Party]]\n", "name_user": "CJK09", "label": "safe", "comment": "Oxford comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephens%E2%80%93Townsend%E2%80%93Murphy_Party"}
{"title_page": "Gortullaghan", "text_new": "[[File:Looking from Gortmore into Gortullaghan Townland (geograph 3597258).jpg|thumb|View of Gortullaghan from Gortmore]]\n'''Gortullaghan''' ({{Irish derived place name|Gort Tulach\u00e1in meaning 'Field of the Little Hillocks'}}) is a [[townland]] in the [[civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of [[Templeport]], [[County Cavan]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It lies in the Roman Catholic parish of [[Templeport]] and barony of [[Tullyhaw]].\n\n==Geography==\n\nGortullaghan is bounded on the north by [[Dunglave]] in [[Swanlinbar]] parish and [[Derrynacreeve]] townland in [[Corlough]] parish, on the west by [[Tawnagh]] townland in [[Corlough]] parish, on the south by [[Mullaghlea]] townland and on the east by [[Gortmore]] and [[Moherloob]] townlands. Its chief geographical features are a stream, spring wells and dug wells. Gortullaghan is traversed by the national secondary [[N87 road (Ireland)]],  minor roads and rural lanes. \nThe townland covers 171 statute acres.<ref name=\"IreAtlas\"/>\n\n==History==\n\nA sub-division of Gortullaghan is called Tomena ({{Irish derived place name|perhaps Tuaim Aonaigh meaning 'Tumulus of the Fair or Meeting-Place' or Tuaim Maoine meaning 'Tumulus of the Wealth' or Tuaim M\u00f3na  meaning \u2018Tumulus of the Bog\u2019}})  \n\nThe 1609 Baronial Map depicts the townland as ''Gortalachin''.<ref>National Archives Dublin [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documents/mpf1-58.pdf]</ref>\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey spells the name as ''Gartullaghen''.\n\nThe 1665 Down Survey map depicts it as ''Gortinelechin''.<ref>Trinity College Dublin: [http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#bm=Tullaghhagh&c=Cavan&indexOfObjectValue=-1&indexOfObjectValueSubstring=-1 The Down Survey of Ireland.]</ref> \n\n[[William Petty]]'s map of 1685 depicts it as ''Gortenelehin''.\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the proprietor being ''Mr Henry Pigott'' and the tenant being ''Farell Duffe McBrian''.\n\nA grant dated 30 January 1668 from King [[Charles II of England]] to Richard Pyett included, inter alia, ''lands of Gortallaghan containing 41 acres 2 roods and 27 perches''.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1244157-1001#page/n121/mode/2up/search/evallaghmore]</ref> \n\nA grant dated 9 March 1669 from King [[Charles II of England]] to [[Arthur Annesley, 1st Earl of Anglesey]] included, inter alia, ''lands in the south part of Gortinelethin alias Gortinedickin containing 24 acres 1 rood and 13 perches at an annual rent of \u00a30-6s-5 1/2d''.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1244157-1001#page/n185/mode/2up/search/Aughweenagh]</ref> \n\nA lease dated 23 December 1720 from [[Morley Saunders]] to Thomas Enery of Bawnboy includes the lands of ''Gartullaughin''.<ref>[https://irishdeedsindex.net/mem.php?memorial=17746]</ref>\n\nA lease dated 10 December 1774 from William Crookshank to John Enery of Bawnboy includes the lands of ''Gortallaughin''.<ref>[https://irishdeedsindex.net/mem.php?memorial=203802]</ref> as does a further deed dated 13 December 1774.<ref>[https://irishdeedsindex.net/mem.php?memorial=204272]</ref>\n\nThe Tithe Applotment Books for 1827 list seventeen tithepayers in the townland.<ref>[http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Gortalaghan&search=Search] [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Gorlataghan&search=Search]  [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Tomony&search=Search] [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Gorlalaghan&search=Search]</ref>\n\nThe Gortullaghan Valuation Office Field books are available for September 1839.<ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00261.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00262.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00263.pdf]</ref>\n\nIn 1841 the population of the townland was 77, being 32 males and 45 females. There were fifteen houses in the townland, all of which were inhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n\nIn 1851 the population of the townland was 62, being 27 males and 35 females, the reduction being due to the Great Famine (Ireland). There were twelve houses in the townland, one of which was uninhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref> \n\n[[Griffith's Valuation]] of 1857 lists twenty one landholders in the townland.<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/griffith-valuation/index.xml?action=doNameSearch&PlaceID=191050&county=Cavan&barony=Tullyhaw&parish=Templeport&townland=%3Cb%3EGortullaghan%3C/b%3E]</ref>\n\nIn 1861 the population of the townland was 56, being 27 males and 29 females. There were eleven houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951p00771975o;view=1up;seq=109;size=175]</ref>\n\nIn 1871 the population of the townland was 41, being 15 males and 26 females. There were seven houses in the townland and all were inhabited.<ref>[https://ia800200.us.archive.org/3/items/op1250167-1001/op1250167-1001.pdf]</ref>\n\nIn 1881 the population of the townland was 26, being 11 males and 15 females. There were seven houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1251357-1001#page/n295/mode/2up]</ref>\n\nIn 1891 the population of the townland was 23, being 9 males and 14 females. There were six houses in the townland, all were inhabited.<ref>[http://www.histpop.org/ohpr/servlet/PageBrowser?path=Browse/Census%20(by%20geography)/Ireland/1891&active=yes&mno=442&tocstate=expandnew&display=sections&display=tables&display=pagetitles&pageseq=296&zoom=4]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1901|1901 census of Ireland]], there are ten families listed in the townland,\n<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1901/Cavan/Tiercahoin/Gortullaghan/]</ref> and in the [[Census of Ireland, 1911|1911 census of Ireland]], there are twelve families listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Cavan/Tircahan/Gortullaghan/ ''Census of Ireland 1911'']</ref>\n\nFolklore from Gortullaghan in the 1930s is available at-<ref>[https://www.duchas.ie/en/cbes/5044787]</ref>\n\n==Tomena School==\n\nThe book Bawnboy and Templeport History Heritage Folklore by Chris Maguire gives the following description of the school-\n\n''Tomena National School. Taken under the National Board 27 July 1848. There was a teachers' residence attached to the schoolroom. The residence was burned about 1880 and two nephews of the teacher, Mrs. McManus, lost their lives in the fire. Later on the residence became a schoolroom, and Tomena a two-teacher school. A fire in 1944 destroyed the original schoolroom and two teachers had to work in the same room until the new school was built in 1953. Principals in Tomena N.S.- Thomas McPartlan (1848-'51); John Baxter; Hugh McManus, Tirnawannagh; Mrs. McManus; Mrs. Lunney; Mrs. O'Hara; Michael Byrne; Chris Maguire (1937-'42); Rose Maguire (1942-'47); Nuala Waldron (1947-'48); Chris Maguire (1948-'56); Se\u00e1n Lennon (1956-'59); C\u00e1it Curran ; Mrs. John F. McGovern; Mrs. Grace Doonan. Assistant Teachers:- Miss Farmer; Philomena O'Dowd; Mrs. Cornyn.''<ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/History-Heritage-Folklore/pages/templeport-schools.html]</ref>\n\nThe Reports from the Commissioners of National Education in Ireland give the following figures for Tomena School, Roll No. 5306-\n\n1854: One male teacher who received an annual salary of \u00a312. There were 73 pupils, 35 boys and 38 girls.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=N6YSAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA383&dq=tullyveela&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwie6eG9vrfZAhWJh6YKHc66AeUQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=templeport&f=false]</ref>\n\n1862: Hugh McManus was the headmaster, a Roman Catholic. There were 121 pupils, all Roman Catholic apart from 12 who were Church of Ireland. The Catechism was taught to the Catholic pupils on Saturdays from 11am to 12 noon.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=nSVcAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA110&dq=garvalt+school+cavan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjn-Mna9NThAhWBShUIHWvbCboQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=garvalt%20&f=false]</ref> \n\n1874: There were now two schools, one for boys and one for girls. Tomena Boys School. One male teacher who received an annual salary of \u00a330. There were 92 male pupils. Tullybrack Girls School, Roll No. 10889. One female teacher who received an annual salary of \u00a320. There were 75 female pupils.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CCxcAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA62&dq=garvolt+cavan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiryOyK8tThAhXSTxUIHXTYAsQQ6AEIPTAE#v=onepage&q=garvolt%20cavan&f=false]</ref>\n\n1890: There were 85 pupils in the boys' school.<ref>[http://www.dippam.ac.uk/eppi/documents/18746/page/503029]</ref>\n\n==Antiquities==\n\nThe chief structures of historical interest in the townland are the sites of Tomena National School and Derrynacreeve Post Office. The site of the tumulus is not known.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"IreAtlas\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ |title=IreAtlas |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ The IreAtlas Townland Data Base]\n\n\n{{County Cavan}}\n{{Coord|54.07514|-7.810271|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Cavan]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Looking from Gortmore into Gortullaghan Townland (geograph 3597258).jpg|thumb|View of Gortullaghan from Gortmore]]\n'''Gortullaghan''' ({{Irish derived place name|Gort Tulach\u00e1in meaning 'Field of the Little Hillocks'}}) is a [[townland]] in the [[civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] of [[Templeport]], [[County Cavan]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It lies in the Roman Catholic parish of [[Templeport]] and barony of [[Tullyhaw]].\n\n==Geography==\n\nGortullaghan is bounded on the north by Dunglave in [[Swanlinbar]] parish and [[Derrynacreeve]] townland in [[Corlough]] parish, on the west by [[Tawnagh]] townland in [[Corlough]] parish, on the south by [[Mullaghlea]] townland and on the east by [[Gortmore]] and [[Moherloob]] townlands. Its chief geographical features are a stream, spring wells and dug wells. Gortullaghan is traversed by the national secondary [[N87 road (Ireland)]],  minor roads and rural lanes. \nThe townland covers 171 statute acres.<ref name=\"IreAtlas\"/>\n\n==History==\n\nA sub-division of Gortullaghan is called Tomena ({{Irish derived place name|perhaps Tuaim Aonaigh meaning 'Tumulus of the Fair or Meeting-Place' or Tuaim Maoine meaning 'Tumulus of the Wealth' or Tuaim M\u00f3na  meaning \u2018Tumulus of the Bog\u2019}})  \n\nThe 1609 Baronial Map depicts the townland as ''Gortalachin''.<ref>National Archives Dublin [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documents/mpf1-58.pdf]</ref>\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey spells the name as ''Gartullaghen''.\n\nThe 1665 Down Survey map depicts it as ''Gortinelechin''.<ref>Trinity College Dublin: [http://downsurvey.tcd.ie/down-survey-maps.php#bm=Tullaghhagh&c=Cavan&indexOfObjectValue=-1&indexOfObjectValueSubstring=-1 The Down Survey of Ireland.]</ref> \n\n[[William Petty]]'s map of 1685 depicts it as ''Gortenelehin''.\n\nThe 1652 Commonwealth Survey lists the proprietor being ''Mr Henry Pigott'' and the tenant being ''Farell Duffe McBrian''.\n\nA grant dated 30 January 1668 from King [[Charles II of England]] to Richard Pyett included, inter alia, ''lands of Gortallaghan containing 41 acres 2 roods and 27 perches''.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1244157-1001#page/n121/mode/2up/search/evallaghmore]</ref> \n\nA grant dated 9 March 1669 from King [[Charles II of England]] to [[Arthur Annesley, 1st Earl of Anglesey]] included, inter alia, ''lands in the south part of Gortinelethin alias Gortinedickin containing 24 acres 1 rood and 13 perches at an annual rent of \u00a30-6s-5 1/2d''.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1244157-1001#page/n185/mode/2up/search/Aughweenagh]</ref> \n\nA lease dated 23 December 1720 from [[Morley Saunders]] to Thomas Enery of Bawnboy includes the lands of ''Gartullaughin''.<ref>[https://irishdeedsindex.net/mem.php?memorial=17746]</ref>\n\nA lease dated 10 December 1774 from William Crookshank to John Enery of Bawnboy includes the lands of ''Gortallaughin''.<ref>[https://irishdeedsindex.net/mem.php?memorial=203802]</ref> as does a further deed dated 13 December 1774.<ref>[https://irishdeedsindex.net/mem.php?memorial=204272]</ref>\n\nThe Tithe Applotment Books for 1827 list seventeen tithepayers in the townland.<ref>[http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Gortalaghan&search=Search] [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Gorlataghan&search=Search]  [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Tomony&search=Search] [http://titheapplotmentbooks.nationalarchives.ie/search/tab/results.jsp?county=Cavan&parish=Templeport&townland=Gorlalaghan&search=Search]</ref>\n\nThe Gortullaghan Valuation Office Field books are available for September 1839.<ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00261.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00262.pdf]</ref><ref>[http://census.nationalarchives.ie/reels/vob/IRE_CENSUS_1821-51_007246947_00263.pdf]</ref>\n\nIn 1841 the population of the townland was 77, being 32 males and 45 females. There were fifteen houses in the townland, all of which were inhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref>\n\nIn 1851 the population of the townland was 62, being 27 males and 35 females, the reduction being due to the Great Famine (Ireland). There were twelve houses in the townland, one of which was uninhabited.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=96RbAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA95&dq=leitra+cavan+-lyrics&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIiq76x9rZAhXLDewKHexcCA0Q6AEIPjAE#v=onepage&q=leitra%20&f=false]</ref> \n\n[[Griffith's Valuation]] of 1857 lists twenty one landholders in the townland.<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/griffith-valuation/index.xml?action=doNameSearch&PlaceID=191050&county=Cavan&barony=Tullyhaw&parish=Templeport&townland=%3Cb%3EGortullaghan%3C/b%3E]</ref>\n\nIn 1861 the population of the townland was 56, being 27 males and 29 females. There were eleven houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=umn.31951p00771975o;view=1up;seq=109;size=175]</ref>\n\nIn 1871 the population of the townland was 41, being 15 males and 26 females. There were seven houses in the townland and all were inhabited.<ref>[https://ia800200.us.archive.org/3/items/op1250167-1001/op1250167-1001.pdf]</ref>\n\nIn 1881 the population of the townland was 26, being 11 males and 15 females. There were seven houses in the townland, of which one was uninhabited.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/op1251357-1001#page/n295/mode/2up]</ref>\n\nIn 1891 the population of the townland was 23, being 9 males and 14 females. There were six houses in the townland, all were inhabited.<ref>[http://www.histpop.org/ohpr/servlet/PageBrowser?path=Browse/Census%20(by%20geography)/Ireland/1891&active=yes&mno=442&tocstate=expandnew&display=sections&display=tables&display=pagetitles&pageseq=296&zoom=4]</ref>\n\nIn the [[Census of Ireland, 1901|1901 census of Ireland]], there are ten families listed in the townland,\n<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1901/Cavan/Tiercahoin/Gortullaghan/]</ref> and in the [[Census of Ireland, 1911|1911 census of Ireland]], there are twelve families listed in the townland.<ref>[http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Cavan/Tircahan/Gortullaghan/ ''Census of Ireland 1911'']</ref>\n\nFolklore from Gortullaghan in the 1930s is available at-<ref>[https://www.duchas.ie/en/cbes/5044787]</ref>\n\n==Tomena School==\n\nThe book Bawnboy and Templeport History Heritage Folklore by Chris Maguire gives the following description of the school-\n\n''Tomena National School. Taken under the National Board 27 July 1848. There was a teachers' residence attached to the schoolroom. The residence was burned about 1880 and two nephews of the teacher, Mrs. McManus, lost their lives in the fire. Later on the residence became a schoolroom, and Tomena a two-teacher school. A fire in 1944 destroyed the original schoolroom and two teachers had to work in the same room until the new school was built in 1953. Principals in Tomena N.S.- Thomas McPartlan (1848-'51); John Baxter; Hugh McManus, Tirnawannagh; Mrs. McManus; Mrs. Lunney; Mrs. O'Hara; Michael Byrne; Chris Maguire (1937-'42); Rose Maguire (1942-'47); Nuala Waldron (1947-'48); Chris Maguire (1948-'56); Se\u00e1n Lennon (1956-'59); C\u00e1it Curran ; Mrs. John F. McGovern; Mrs. Grace Doonan. Assistant Teachers:- Miss Farmer; Philomena O'Dowd; Mrs. Cornyn.''<ref>[http://www.bawnboy.com/History-Heritage-Folklore/pages/templeport-schools.html]</ref>\n\nThe Reports from the Commissioners of National Education in Ireland give the following figures for Tomena School, Roll No. 5306-\n\n1854: One male teacher who received an annual salary of \u00a312. There were 73 pupils, 35 boys and 38 girls.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=N6YSAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA383&dq=tullyveela&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwie6eG9vrfZAhWJh6YKHc66AeUQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=templeport&f=false]</ref>\n\n1862: Hugh McManus was the headmaster, a Roman Catholic. There were 121 pupils, all Roman Catholic apart from 12 who were Church of Ireland. The Catechism was taught to the Catholic pupils on Saturdays from 11am to 12 noon.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=nSVcAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA110&dq=garvalt+school+cavan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjn-Mna9NThAhWBShUIHWvbCboQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=garvalt%20&f=false]</ref> \n\n1874: There were now two schools, one for boys and one for girls. Tomena Boys School. One male teacher who received an annual salary of \u00a330. There were 92 male pupils. Tullybrack Girls School, Roll No. 10889. One female teacher who received an annual salary of \u00a320. There were 75 female pupils.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CCxcAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA62&dq=garvolt+cavan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiryOyK8tThAhXSTxUIHXTYAsQQ6AEIPTAE#v=onepage&q=garvolt%20cavan&f=false]</ref>\n\n1890: There were 85 pupils in the boys' school.<ref>[http://www.dippam.ac.uk/eppi/documents/18746/page/503029]</ref>\n\n==Antiquities==\n\nThe chief structures of historical interest in the townland are the sites of Tomena National School and Derrynacreeve Post Office. The site of the tumulus is not known.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"IreAtlas\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ |title=IreAtlas |accessdate=29 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thecore.com/seanruad/ The IreAtlas Townland Data Base]\n\n\n{{County Cavan}}\n{{Coord|54.07514|-7.810271|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Townlands of County Cavan]]\n", "name_user": "Cormac1cormac1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gortullaghan"}
{"title_page": "Civic United Front", "text_new": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Civic United Front\n| native_name = {{native name|sw|Chama Cha Wananchi}}\n| logo = CUF partylogo.png\n| logo_size = 100px\n| colorcode = #00BFFF\n| abbreviation = CUF\n| chairman = [[Ibrahim Haruna Lipumba]]\n| secretary_general = \n| spokesperson = \n| founder = \n| slogan = ''Equal rights for all <br>{{small|(Haki sawa kwa wote)}}''<ref name=\"BurgessIssa2009\">{{cite book|author1=G. Thomas Burgess|author2=Ali Sultan Issa|author3=Seif Sharif Hamad|title=Race, Revolution, and the Struggle for Human Rights in Zanzibar: The Memoirs of Ali Sultan Issa and Seif Sharif Hamad|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D3ZJRmX_uoMC&pg=PA266|year=2009|publisher=Ohio University Press|isbn=978-0-8214-1851-2|pages=266\u2013}}</ref>\n| founded = {{start date|1992|5|28|df=y}}\n| merger = Civic Movement<br>Zanzibar United Front\n| headquarters = [[Zanzibar City|Zanzibar]]\n| newspaper = \n| think_tank = \n| student_wing = \n| youth_wing = \n| wing1_title = \n| wing1 = \n| wing2_title = \n| wing2 = \n| membership_year = \n| membership = \n| ideology = [[Zanzibari autonomism]]<br>[[Liberalism]]\n| position = [[Centrism|Centre]]\n| national = \n| international = [[Liberal International|LI]]\n| affiliation1_title = African affiliation\n| affiliation1 = [[Africa Liberal Network|ALN]]\n| colours = {{colour box|#00BFFF}} {{colour box|red}}\n| anthem = \n| seats1_title = [[National Assembly (Tanzania)|National Assembly]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|{{TanzNA|CUF}}|393|hex=#00BFFF}}\n| seats2_title = [[Zanzibar House of Representatives|Zanzibar HoR]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|0|85|hex=#00BFFF}}\n| seats3_title = [[East African Legislative Assembly|EALA]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|1|9|hex=#00BFFF}}\n| seats4_title = [[SADC Parliamentary Forum|SADC PF]]\n| seats4 = {{Composition bar|1|5|hex=#00BFFF}}\n| seats5_title = [[Pan-African Parliament]]\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|0|5|hex=#00BFFF}}\n| symbol = A pair of [[shaking hands]]<br>underneath the Scales of Justice\n| flag = Civic United Front Flag.jpg\n| website = {{URL|http://www.cuftz.com/|Political Party Website}}\n| country = Tanzania\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\nThe '''Civic United Front''' ('''CUF'''; [[Kiswahili]]: ''Chama Cha Wananchi'', literally: Party of Citizens) is a [[liberal parties|liberal party]] in [[Tanzania]]. Although nationally based, most of the CUF's support comes from the [[Zanzibar]] islands of [[Unguja]] and [[Pemba, Tanzania|Pemba]].<ref>{{cite book|author=John Ndembwike|title=Tanzania: Profile of a Nation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lqcHBZ_0n6gC&pg=PA119|year=2009|publisher=New Africa Press|isbn=978-9987-9308-1-4|pages=119\u2013}}</ref> The party is a member of [[Liberal International]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liberal-international.org/members/cuf_tanzania/|title=Civic United Front at Liberal International|publisher=Liberal International}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Civic United Front was formed on 28 May 1992 through a merger of two formerly existing movements - KAMAHURU, a pressure group for democratization in Zanzibar, and the Civic Movement, a human rights organization based on the mainland.\n\nMany CUF leaders were former stalwarts of the ruling [[Chama Cha Mapinduzi]] (CCM), some of whom had been expelled over disputes about party and government policy. The party received full recognition on 21 January 1993.\n\n==Leadership==\n* [[Ibrahim Lipumba]], National Chairman\n* [[Abass Juma Muhunzi]], Vice Chairman <ref>{{cite web|title=Tanzania: High Court rules Prof Lipumba is CUF chairman|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Tanzania--High-Court-rules-Prof-Lipumba-is-CUF-chairman/1840340-5030472-uuuk3t/index.html|website=The Citizen|date=18 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Magdalena Sakaya]], Deputy Secretary General (Tanzania mainland)\n* [[Nassor Mazrui]], Deputy Secretary General (Zanzibar)\n\n==Electoral performance==\n[[File:Ibrahim Lipumba 2003.jpg|thumb|left|Lipumba (left) and Hamad (right) at a press conference in Pemba after their victory in a by-election]]\nThe Civic United Front participated in the [[Tanzanian general election, 1995|1995]], [[Tanzanian general election, 2000|2000]], [[Tanzanian general election, 2005|2005]], [[Tanzanian general election, 2010|2010]] and [[Tanzanian general election, 2015|2015]] elections.\n\nIn the 1995 presidential election, CUF candidate Ibrahim Lipumba placed third (behind [[Benjamin Mkapa]] of the CCM and [[National Convention for Construction and Reform-Mageuzi|NCCR-Mageuzi]] candidate [[Augustine Mrema]]) winning 6.43% of the vote. In the National Assembly, the party won 24 of 232 elective seats, making it the largest opposition party in the legislature. Seif Shariff Hamad won 49.76% of the vote against 50.24% for the ruling party's Salmin Amour in elections for the presidency of Zanzibar. The CUF also obtained 24 of 50 elective seats in the Zanzibar House of Representatives. International and domestic observers heavily criticized the conduct of the Zanzibar polls.\n\nFollowing the election, the CUF boycotted the House of Representatives and refused to recognize the Zanzibari government as legitimate. In November 1997, eighteen leaders of the CUF were arrested and subsequently charged with [[treason]]. These charges were later dropped.\n\nIn the 29 October 2000 presidential election, Lipumba placed second to Mkapa, winning 16.26% of the vote. The party maintained its status as the largest opposition party in the National Assembly by winning 17 of 231 elective seats. Seif Shariff Hamad won 32.96% of the vote against 67.04% for the ruling party's [[Amani Abeid Karume]] in elections for the presidency of Zanzibar. The CUF won 16 of 50 elective seats in the Zanzibar House of Representatives. The elections were considered largely free and fair on the mainland, but observers noted serious irregularities in the Zanzibar polls, with some calling for a complete re-run of the polls. When the electoral commission nullified the results in only 16 constituencies, the CUF announced that it would boycott the new elections conducted on 5 November 2000.\n\n[[Image:CUF Office in Pemba.JPG|thumb|A CUF party office in Chake Chake, Pemba]]\nElections for the Zanzibar Presidency and House of Representatives took place on 30 October 2005. Seif Shariff Hamad placed second to incumbent Amani Abeid Karume, winning 46.07% of the vote. The party won 19 seats in the House of Representatives.\n\n[[Tanzanian elections, 2005|National elections]] were held on 14 December 2005. [[Ibrahim Lipumba]] placed a distant second to CCM candidate [[Jakaya Kikwete]], winning 11.68% of the vote. Out of the 232 National Assembly seats filled through direct election, the CUF won 19.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://cuftz.com/}}\n\n{{Tanzania political parties}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Political parties in Tanzania]]\n[[Category:1992 establishments in Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Liberal parties in Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Politics of Zanzibar]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1992]]\n[[Category:Members of the Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox political party\n| name = Civic United Front\n| native_name = {{native name|sw|Chama Cha Wananchi}}\n| logo = CUF partylogo.png\n| logo_size = 100px\n| colorcode = #00BFFF\n| abbreviation = CUF\n| chairman = [[Ibrahim Haruna Lipumba]]\n| secretary_general = \n| spokesperson = \n| founder = \n| slogan = ''Equal rights for all <br>{{small|(Haki sawa kwa wote)}}''<ref name=\"BurgessIssa2009\">{{cite book|author1=G. Thomas Burgess|author2=Ali Sultan Issa|author3=Seif Sharif Hamad|title=Race, Revolution, and the Struggle for Human Rights in Zanzibar: The Memoirs of Ali Sultan Issa and Seif Sharif Hamad|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D3ZJRmX_uoMC&pg=PA266|year=2009|publisher=Ohio University Press|isbn=978-0-8214-1851-2|pages=266\u2013}}</ref>\n| founded = {{start date|1992|5|28|df=y}}\n| merger = Civic Movement<br>Zanzibar United Front\n| headquarters = [[Zanzibar City|Zanzibar]]\n| newspaper = \n| think_tank = \n| student_wing = \n| youth_wing = \n| wing1_title = \n| wing1 = \n| wing2_title = \n| wing2 = \n| membership_year = \n| membership = \n| ideology = [[Zanzibari autonomism]]<br>[[Liberalism]]\n| position = [[Centrism|Centre]]\n| national = \n| international = [[Liberal International|LI]]\n| affiliation1_title = African affiliation\n| affiliation1 = [[Africa Liberal Network|ALN]]\n| colours = {{colour box|#00BFFF}} {{colour box|red}}\n| anthem = \n| seats1_title = [[National Assembly (Tanzania)|National Assembly]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|{{TanzNA|CUF}}|393|hex=#00BFFF}}\n| seats2_title = [[Zanzibar House of Representatives|Zanzibar HoR]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|0|85|hex=#00BFFF}}\n| seats3_title = [[East African Legislative Assembly|EALA]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|1|9|hex=#00BFFF}}\n| seats4_title = [[SADC Parliamentary Forum|SADC PF]]\n| seats4 = {{Composition bar|1|5|hex=#00BFFF}}\n| seats5_title = [[Pan-African Parliament]]\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|0|5|hex=#00BFFF}}\n| symbol = A pair of [[shaking hands]]<br>underneath the Scales of Justice\n| flag = Civic United Front Flag.jpg\n| website = {{URL|http://www.cuftz.com/|Political Party Website}}\n| country = Tanzania\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\nThe '''Civic United Front''' ('''CUF'''; [[Kiswahili]]: ''Chama Cha Wananchi'', literally: Party of Citizens) is a [[liberal parties|liberal party]] in [[Tanzania]]. Although nationally based, most of the CUF's support comes from the [[Zanzibar]] islands of [[Unguja]] and [[Pemba, Tanzania|Pemba]].<ref>{{cite book|author=John Ndembwike|title=Tanzania: Profile of a Nation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lqcHBZ_0n6gC&pg=PA119|year=2009|publisher=New Africa Press|isbn=978-9987-9308-1-4|pages=119\u2013}}</ref> The party is a member of [[Liberal International]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liberal-international.org/members/cuf_tanzania/|title=Civic United Front at Liberal International|publisher=Liberal International}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Civic United Front was formed on 28 May 1992 through a merger of two formerly existing movements - KAMAHURU, a pressure group for democratization in Zanzibar, and the Civic Movement, a human rights organization based on the mainland.\n\nMany CUF leaders were former stalwarts of the ruling [[Chama Cha Mapinduzi]] (CCM), some of whom had been expelled over disputes about party and government policy. The party received full recognition on 21 January 1993.\n\n==Leadership==\n* [[Ibrahim Lipumba]], National Chairman\n* [[Abass Juma Muhunzi]], Ex-Vice Chairman <ref>{{cite web|title=Tanzania: High Court rules Prof Lipumba is CUF chairman|url=https://www.thecitizen.co.tz/news/Tanzania--High-Court-rules-Prof-Lipumba-is-CUF-chairman/1840340-5030472-uuuk3t/index.html|website=The Citizen|date=18 March 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Magdalena Sakaya]], Deputy Secretary General (Tanzania mainland)\n* [[Nassor Mazrui]], Deputy Secretary General (Zanzibar)\n\n==Electoral performance==\n[[File:Ibrahim Lipumba 2003.jpg|thumb|left|Lipumba (left) and Hamad (right) at a press conference in Pemba after their victory in a by-election]]\nThe Civic United Front participated in the [[Tanzanian general election, 1995|1995]], [[Tanzanian general election, 2000|2000]], [[Tanzanian general election, 2005|2005]], [[Tanzanian general election, 2010|2010]] and [[Tanzanian general election, 2015|2015]] elections.\n\nIn the 1995 presidential election, CUF candidate Ibrahim Lipumba placed third (behind [[Benjamin Mkapa]] of the CCM and [[National Convention for Construction and Reform-Mageuzi|NCCR-Mageuzi]] candidate [[Augustine Mrema]]) winning 6.43% of the vote. In the National Assembly, the party won 24 of 232 elective seats, making it the largest opposition party in the legislature. Seif Shariff Hamad won 49.76% of the vote against 50.24% for the ruling party's Salmin Amour in elections for the presidency of Zanzibar. The CUF also obtained 24 of 50 elective seats in the Zanzibar House of Representatives. International and domestic observers heavily criticized the conduct of the Zanzibar polls.\n\nFollowing the election, the CUF boycotted the House of Representatives and refused to recognize the Zanzibari government as legitimate. In November 1997, eighteen leaders of the CUF were arrested and subsequently charged with [[treason]]. These charges were later dropped.\n\nIn the 29 October 2000 presidential election, Lipumba placed second to Mkapa, winning 16.26% of the vote. The party maintained its status as the largest opposition party in the National Assembly by winning 17 of 231 elective seats. Seif Shariff Hamad won 32.96% of the vote against 67.04% for the ruling party's [[Amani Abeid Karume]] in elections for the presidency of Zanzibar. The CUF won 16 of 50 elective seats in the Zanzibar House of Representatives. The elections were considered largely free and fair on the mainland, but observers noted serious irregularities in the Zanzibar polls, with some calling for a complete re-run of the polls. When the electoral commission nullified the results in only 16 constituencies, the CUF announced that it would boycott the new elections conducted on 5 November 2000.\n\n[[Image:CUF Office in Pemba.JPG|thumb|A CUF party office in Chake Chake, Pemba]]\nElections for the Zanzibar Presidency and House of Representatives took place on 30 October 2005. Seif Shariff Hamad placed second to incumbent Amani Abeid Karume, winning 46.07% of the vote. The party won 19 seats in the House of Representatives.\n\n[[Tanzanian elections, 2005|National elections]] were held on 14 December 2005. [[Ibrahim Lipumba]] placed a distant second to CCM candidate [[Jakaya Kikwete]], winning 11.68% of the vote. Out of the 232 National Assembly seats filled through direct election, the CUF won 19.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://cuftz.com/}}\n\n{{Tanzania political parties}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Political parties in Tanzania]]\n[[Category:1992 establishments in Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Liberal parties in Tanzania]]\n[[Category:Politics of Zanzibar]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1992]]\n[[Category:Members of the Unrepresented Nations and Peoples Organization]]\n", "name_user": "Kirutu", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civic_United_Front"}
{"title_page": "Am\u00e9lie", "text_new": "{{redirect|Amelie||Am\u00e9lie (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|2001 film directed by Jean-Pierre Jeunet}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Am\u00e9lie\n| image          = Amelie poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = French theatrical poster\n| director       = [[Jean-Pierre Jeunet]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Jean-Marc Deschamps\n* Claudie Ossard\n}}\n| screenplay     = Guillaume Laurant\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Guillaume Laurant\n* Jean-Pierre Jeunet\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Audrey Tautou]]\n* [[Mathieu Kassovitz]]\n* [[Rufus (actor)|Rufus]]\n* [[Lorella Cravotta]]\n* [[Serge Merlin]]\n* [[Jamel Debbouze]]\n* [[Claire Maurier]]\n* [[Clotilde Mollet]]\n* [[Isabelle Nanty]]\n* [[Dominique Pinon]]\n* [[Artus de Penguern]]\n* [[Yolande Moreau]]\n* [[Urbain Cancelier]]\n* [[Maurice B\u00e9nichou]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Yann Tiersen]]\n| cinematography = [[Bruno Delbonnel]]\n| editing        = [[Herv\u00e9 Schneid]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Canal+]]\n* [[France 3 Cin\u00e9ma]]\n* [[UGC (cinema operator)|UGC]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[UGC-Fox Distribution]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2001|04|25|France|2001|08|16|Germany}}\n| runtime        = 123 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 122:43--><ref>{{cite web|title=''AMELIE FROM MONTMARTRE (LE FABULEUX DESTIN D'AMELIE POULAIN)'' (15)|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/amelie-montmartre-le-fabuleux-destin-damelie-poulain-2001|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=17 July 2001|accessdate=13 April 2013}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* France\n* Germany\n}}\n| language       = French\n| budget         = $10&nbsp;million<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n| gross          = $174.2&nbsp;million<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web |url= http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Fabuleux-destin-d-Amelie-Poulain-Le#tab=summary |title=Am\u00e9lie (2001) | work = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |publisher= [[IMDb]]  |accessdate=25 September 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Am\u00e9lie''''' (also known as '''''Le Fabuleux Destin d'Am\u00e9lie Poulain'''''; {{IPA-fr|l\u0259 fabyl\u00f8 dest\u025b\u0303 d\u203fameli pul\u025b\u0303}}; {{lang-en|The Fabulous Destiny of Am\u00e9lie Poulain|italic=yes}}) is a 2001 French [[romantic comedy]] film directed by [[Jean-Pierre Jeunet]]. Written by Jeunet with Guillaume Laurant, the film is a whimsical depiction of contemporary Parisian life, set in [[Montmartre]]. It tells the story of a shy waitress, played by [[Audrey Tautou]], who decides to change the lives of those around her for the better while struggling with her own isolation. The film was a [[International co-production|co-production]] between companies in [[Cinema of France|France]] and [[Cinema of Germany|Germany]]. Taking in over $33&nbsp;million in a limited theatrical release, it is to date the highest-grossing French-language film released in the United States, and one of the biggest international successes for a French movie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=foreign.htm&sort=gross&order=DESC&p=.htm |title=Foreign Language Movies at the Box Office |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe film received critical acclaim and was a major box office success. ''Am\u00e9lie'' won [[European Film Award for Best Film|Best Film]] at the [[European Film Awards]]; it also won four [[C\u00e9sar Award]]s in 2002 (including [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film|Best Film]] and [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Director|Best Director]]), two [[55th British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Awards]] (including [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]), and was nominated for five [[Academy Awards]].\n\n==Plot==\n[[File:Paris - Caf\u00e9 des 2 Moulins - 2004.jpg|thumb|left|Am\u00e9lie works at the [[Caf\u00e9 des 2 Moulins]] in Montmartre]]\n\nAm\u00e9lie Poulain is born in June 1974 and brought up by eccentric parents who \u2013 incorrectly believing that she has a heart defect \u2013 decide to home-school her. To cope with her loneliness, Am\u00e9lie develops an active imagination and a mischievous personality. When Am\u00e9lie is six, her mother, Amandine, is killed when a suicidal Canadian tourist jumps from the roof of [[Notre-Dame de Paris]] and lands on her. As a result, her father Rapha\u00ebl ([[Rufus (actor)|Rufus]]) withdraws more and more from society. Am\u00e9lie leaves home at the age of 18 and becomes a waitress at the [[Caf\u00e9 des 2 Moulins]] in [[Montmartre]], which is staffed and frequented by a collection of eccentrics. She is single and lets her imagination roam freely, finding contentment in simple pleasures like dipping her hand into grain sacks and cracking [[cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e]] with a spoon.\n\nOn 31 August 1997, startled by the news of the [[death of Diana, Princess of Wales]], Am\u00e9lie drops a plastic perfume-stopper, which dislodges a wall tile and accidentally reveals an old metal box of childhood memorabilia hidden by a boy who lived in her apartment decades earlier. Am\u00e9lie resolves to track down the boy and return the box to him. She promises herself that if it makes him happy, she will devote her life to bringing happiness to others.\n\nAfter asking the apartment's concierge and several old tenants about the boy's identity, Am\u00e9lie meets her reclusive neighbour, Raymond Dufayel, an artist with [[Osteogenesis imperfecta|brittle bone disease]] who repaints [[Pierre-Auguste Renoir|Renoir]]'''s [[Luncheon of the Boating Party]]'' every year. He recalls the boy's name as \"Bretodeau\". Am\u00e9lie quickly finds the man, Dominique Bretodeau, and surreptitiously gives him the box. Moved to tears by the discovery and the memories it holds, Bretodeau resolves to reconcile with his estranged daughter and the grandson he has never met. Am\u00e9lie happily embarks on her new mission.\n\nAm\u00e9lie secretly executes complex schemes that affect the lives of those around her. She escorts a blind man to the M\u00e9tro station, giving him a rich description of the street scenes he passes. She persuades her father to follow his dream of touring the world by stealing his [[garden gnome]] and having a flight attendant friend [[airmail]] pictures of it [[Travelling gnome prank|posing with landmarks from all over the world]]. She starts a romance between her hypochondriacal co-worker Georgette and Joseph, one of the customers in the bar. She convinces Madeleine Wallace, the concierge of her block of flats, that the husband who abandoned her had sent her a final conciliatory love letter just before his accidental death years before. She [[Gaslighting|gaslights]] Collignon, the nasty greengrocer. Mentally exhausted, Collignon no longer abuses his meek but good-natured assistant Lucien. A delighted Lucien takes charge at the grocery stand.\n\nMr. Dufayel, having observed Am\u00e9lie, begins a conversation with her about his painting. Although he has copied the same painting 20 times, he has never quite captured the look of the girl drinking a glass of water. They discuss the meaning of this character, and over several conversations, Am\u00e9lie begins projecting her loneliness onto the image. Dufayel recognizes this and uses the girl in the painting to push Am\u00e9lie to examine her attraction to a quirky young man, Nino Quincampoix, who collects the discarded photographs of strangers from passport photo booths. When Am\u00e9lie bumps into Nino a second time, she realizes she is falling in love with him. He accidentally drops a photo album in the street. Am\u00e9lie retrieves it.\n\nAm\u00e9lie plays a cat-and-mouse game with Nino around Paris before returning his treasured album anonymously. After arranging a meeting at the 2 Moulins, Am\u00e9lie panics and tries to deny her identity. Her co-worker, Gina ([[Clotilde Mollet]]), concerned for Am\u00e9lie's well-being, screens Nino for her; Joseph's comment about this misleads Am\u00e9lie to believe she has lost Nino to Gina. It takes Dufayel's insight to give her the courage to pursue Nino, resulting in a romantic night together and the beginning of a relationship. Am\u00e9lie finally finds happiness for herself.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Audrey Tautou]] as Am\u00e9lie Poulain \n** Flora Guiet as young Am\u00e9lie\n* [[Mathieu Kassovitz]] as Nino Quincampoix\n** Amaury Babault as young Nino\n* [[Rufus (actor)|Rufus]] as Rapha\u00ebl Poulain, Am\u00e9lie's father\n* [[Serge Merlin]] as Raymond Dufayel, \"The Glass Man\"\n* [[Lorella Cravotta]] as Amandine Poulain, Am\u00e9lie's mother\n* [[Clotilde Mollet]] as Gina, a fellow waitress\n* [[Claire Maurier]] as Suzanne, the owner of Caf\u00e9 des Deux Moulins\n* [[Isabelle Nanty]] as Georgette, the resident hypochondriac\n* [[Dominique Pinon]] as Joseph\n* [[Artus de Penguern]] as Hipolito, the writer\n* [[Yolande Moreau]] as Madeleine Wallace (Wells, in English subtitled version)\n* [[Urbain Cancelier]] as Collignon, the grocer\n* [[Jamel Debbouze]] as Lucien, the grocer's assistant\n* [[Maurice B\u00e9nichou]] as Dominique Bretodeau\n** Kevin Fernandes as young Dominique\n* [[Michel Robin]] as Mr. Collignon\n* [[Andr\u00e9e Damant]] as Mrs. Collignon\n* [[Claude Perron]] as Eva, Nino's colleague\n* [[Armelle]] as Philom\u00e8ne, air hostess\n* [[Ticky Holgado]] as Man in a photo\n* [[Fabienne Chaudat]] as The woman in a coma\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:20051018\u00c9picerie d'Am\u00e9lie Poulain 2.jpg|thumb|Au March\u00e9 de la Butte, Rue des Trois Fr\u00e8res, Paris, used as the location of Monsieur Collignon's shop]]\n\nIn his [[Audio commentary|DVD commentary]], Jeunet explains that he originally wrote the role of Am\u00e9lie for the English actress [[Emily Watson]]. In that first draft, Am\u00e9lie's father was an Englishman living in London. However, Watson's French was not strong, and when she became unavailable to shoot the film, owing to a conflict with the filming of ''[[Gosford Park]]'', Jeunet rewrote the screenplay for a French actress. [[Audrey Tautou]] was the first actress he auditioned having seen her on the poster for the 1999 film ''[[Venus Beauty Institute]]''.\n\nThe movie was filmed mainly in Paris. The [[Caf\u00e9 des 2 Moulins]] (15 Rue Lepic, Montmartre, Paris) where Am\u00e9lie works is a real place.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Am\u00e9lie: filming locations |work=Movieloci.com |date=23 July 2012 |url=http://www.movieloci.com/281-Amelie-from-Montmartre?snapshot=2794}}</ref>\n\nThe filmmakers made use of [[computer-generated imagery]] (including [[computer animation]]),<ref>{{cite news|last=Arnold|first=William|date=8 November 2001|title=Inspired 'Am\u00e9lie' blends solid comedy with cutting-edge special effects|url=https://www.seattlepi.com/ae/movies/article/Inspired-Amelie-blends-solid-comedy-with-1071154.php|newspaper=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|access-date=8 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/18111/looking-back-at-jean-pierre-jeunets-amelie|title=Looking back at Jean Pierre-Jeunet's Amelie|last=Bond|first=Zoe|date=29 September 2011|publisher=Den of Geek|access-date=8 June 2019}}</ref> and a [[digital intermediate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/ac2005_article/VR1117915901?nav=lenser&categoryid=1804|title=Color schemes: Lensers view new post-prod'n process as an integral tool in their paint box|work=Variety|date=6 January 2005|accessdate=8 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060106232403/http://www.variety.com/ac2005_article/VR1117915901?nav=lenser&categoryid=1804|archivedate=6 January 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> The studio scenes were filmed in the Coloneum Studio in [[Cologne]] (Germany). The film shares many of the themes in the plot with second half of the 1994 film ''[[Chungking Express]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediacircus.net/amelie.html |title=Amelie Movie Review by Anthony Leong from |publisher=MediaCircus.net |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dickerson |first=Jeff |url=http://www.michigandaily.com/content/audrey-tautou-and-french-film-amelie-are-pure-movie-magic |title=Audrey Tautou and French film `Amelie' are pure movie magic |newspaper=[[The Michigan Daily]] |date=10 April 2002 |accessdate=9 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released in France, Belgium, and [[Romandy|French-speaking western Switzerland]] in April 2001, with subsequent screenings at various film festivals followed by releases around the world. It received [[limited release]]s in North America, the United Kingdom, and [[Australasia]] later in 2001.\n\n[[Cannes Film Festival]] selector Gilles Jacob described ''Am\u00e9lie'' as \"uninteresting\", and therefore it was not screened at the festival, although the version he viewed was an early cut without music. The absence of ''Am\u00e9lie'' at the festival caused something of a controversy because of the warm welcome by the French media and audience in contrast with the reaction of the selector.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tobias |first=Scott |url=http://www.avclub.com/content/node/22708 |title=Jean-Pierre Jeunet |newspaper=The A.V. Club |accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref> David Martin-Jones, in an article in ''[[Senses of Cinema]]'', stated that the film \"[wears] its national [French] identity on its sleeve\" and that this attracted both audiences of mainstream movies and those of [[arthouse]] ones.<ref name=\"Martin-Jones\">{{cite web |title=Review: 'Colombiana: Europa Corp and the Ambiguous Geopolitics of the Action Movie'|work=[[Senses of Cinema]]|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2012/feature-articles/colombiana-europa-corp-and-the-ambiguous-geopolitics-of-the-action-movie/|first=David |last=Martin-Jones |date= 1 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an 89% approval rating, based on 178 reviews, with an average rating of 8.1/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"The feel-good ''Am\u00e9lie'' is a lively, fanciful charmer, showcasing Audrey Tautou as its delightful heroine\".<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/amelie/|title=Am\u00e9lie (2001)|accessdate=10 April 2018|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 69 out of 100, based on 31 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/amelie |title=Am\u00e9lie Reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]  |date=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlan Morrison from [[Empire (film magazine)|''Empire'' Online]] gave ''Am\u00e9lie'' five stars and called it \"one of the year's best, with crossover potential along the lines of ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (1990 film)|Cyrano De Bergerac]]'' and ''[[Il Postino]]''. Given its quirky heart, it might well surpass them all\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/ReviewComplete.asp?FID=7284 |title=Empire's Amelie Movie Review |work=Empire (film magazine) |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref>                                                                    Blogger Sarmad Iqbal from [[International Policy Digest]] commented in his review that \u201cWhat makes this film special is indeed the innocence of the leading protagonist intertwined with her frequent retreats from it.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://intpolicydigest.org/2020/04/04/seven-binge-worthy-french-films-to-get-you-through-self-isolation/ |title=Seven Binge Worthy French Films to Get You Through Self-Isolation |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nPaul Tatara of [[CNN]] praised ''Am\u00e9lie''{{'}}s playful nature. In his review, he wrote, \"Its whimsical, free-ranging nature is often enchanting; the first hour, in particular, is brimming with amiable, sardonic laughs\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Movies/11/07/review.amelie/index.html | publisher=[[CNN]] | title=Review: 'Amelie' is imaginative | date=7 November 2001}}</ref>\n\nThe film was attacked by critic Serge Kaganski of ''[[Les Inrockuptibles]]'' for an unrealistic and picturesque vision of a bygone French society with few [[Minority group|ethnic minorities]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmlinc.com/film-comment/article/the-amelie-effect |title=The Am\u00e9lie Effect |publisher=Filmlinc.com |accessdate=21 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323105658/http://www.filmlinc.com/film-comment/article/the-amelie-effect |archivedate=23 March 2012 }}</ref> Jeunet dismissed the criticism by pointing out that the photo collection contains pictures of people from numerous ethnic backgrounds, and that [[Jamel Debbouze]], who plays Lucien, is of Moroccan descent.\n\n===Awards and nominations=== <!-- fix reference in lead section if this section is renamed -->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"5\"| [[Academy Awards]]<ref name=\"Oscars2002\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/74th-winners.html |title=The 74th Academy Awards (2002) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=19 November 2011|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences}}</ref>\n| [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| [[Jean-Pierre Jeunet]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]\n| Guillaume Laurant and Jean-Pierre Jeunet\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| [[Bruno Delbonnel]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]]\n| [[Aline Bonetto]] and [[Marie-Laure Valla]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]]\n| [[Vincent Arnardi]], [[Guillaume Leriche]], [[Jean Umansky]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"9\"| [[British Academy Film Awards]]\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]\n| Jean-Pierre Jeunet \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress in a Leading Role]]\n| [[Audrey Tautou]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]\n| Guillaume Laurant and Jean-Pierre Jeunet\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| Bruno Delbonnel\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]]\n| Aline Bonetto\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n| [[Herv\u00e9 Schneid]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Music|Best Film Music]]\n| [[Yann Tiersen]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language|Best Film Not in the English Language]]\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"12\"| [[C\u00e9sar Award]]s\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| Jean-Pierre Jeunet \n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| Audrey Tautou\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| [[Jamel Debbouze]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Rufus (actor)|Rufus]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| [[Isabelle Nanty]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Writing|Best Writing]]\n| Guillaume Laurant and Jean-Pierre Jeunet\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| Bruno Delbonnel\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]]\n| Aline Bonetto\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]\n| Madeline Fontaine\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n| Herv\u00e9 Schneid \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Music|Best Music]]\n| Yann Tiersen\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"4\"| [[European Film Awards]]\n| [[European Film Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|rowspan=2| Jean-Pierre Jeunet\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[European Film Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[European Film Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| Audrey Tautou\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[European Film Award for Best Cinematographer|Best Cinematography]]\n| Bruno Delbonnel\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[French Syndicate of Cinema Critics]]\n| Best French Film\n|\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Golden Globe Award]]s\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n|rowspan=2| Jean-Pierre Jeunet\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Karlovy Vary International Film Festival]]\n| [[Crystal Globe]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Toronto International Film Festival]]\n| [[Toronto International Film Festival People's Choice Award|People's Choice Award]]\n| \n| {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\nThe film was selected by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as one of \"The Best 1,000 Movies Ever Made\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/ref/movies/1000best.html | work=The New York Times | title=The Best 1,000 Movies Ever Made | date=29 April 2003 | accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref> The film placed No. 2 in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine's \"The 100 Best Films of World Cinema\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Green |first1=Willow |title=The 100 Best Films Of World Cinema |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/100-greatest-world-cinema-films/ |website=Empire (film magazine) |accessdate=26 July 2019 |date=11 June 2010}}</ref> ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' magazine ranked it second on its list of the 50 Best Movies of the Decade (2000\u20132009).<ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Best Movies of the Decade (2000\u20132009)|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2009/11/50-best-movies-of-the-decade-2000-2009.html|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste Magazine]]|accessdate=14 December 2011|date=3 November 2009}}</ref> In August of that same year, ''[[BBC]] Magazine'' conducted a poll on the 21st century's 100 greatest films so far, with ''Am\u00e9lie'' ranking at number 87.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC Culture \u2013 The 21st Century's 100 greatest films|work=BBC Magazine|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films|date=23 August 2016|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' named the film poster one of the best on its list of the top 25 film posters in the past 25 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20207076_20207387_20207597,00.html |title=Movies: 25 New Classic Posters |work=Entertainment Weekly  |date=27 June 2008 |accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref> It also named Am\u00e9lie setting up a wild goose chase for her beloved Nino all through Paris as No. 9 on its list of top 25 Romantic Gestures.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/gallery/25-most-romantic-gestures-film-0/?slide=341112#341112 |title=New Classics: Romantic Gestures |work=Entertainment Weekly  |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref> In 2010, an online public poll by the ''[[American Cinematographer]]'' \u2013 the house journal of the [[American Society of Cinematographers]] \u2013 named ''Am\u00e9lie'' the best shot film of the decade.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.movieline.com/2010/06/was-amelie-really-the-best-shot-film-of-the-last-decade.php |title=Was Am\u00e9lie Really the Best-Shot Film of the Last Decade? |publisher=movieline.com |date=29 June 2010 |accessdate=5 June 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701041512/http://www.movieline.com/2010/06/was-amelie-really-the-best-shot-film-of-the-last-decade.php |archivedate=1 July 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n''Amelie'' is rated 37 among the 50 Greatest Romantic Comedies of All Time by [[RollingStone]] Magazine<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-lists/50-greatest-romantic-comedies-of-all-time-790068/amelie-2001-792272/ |title=50 Greatest Romantic Comedies of All Time |work=Rolling Stone  |date=14 February 2019 |accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>                             ''Amelie'' is included  among the Seven Binge Worthy French Films to Get Through Self-Isolation by Sarmad Iqbal of [[International Policy Digest]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://intpolicydigest.org/2020/04/04/seven-binge-worthy-french-films-to-get-you-through-self-isolation/ |title= Seven Binge Worthy French Films to Get You Through Self-Isolation|work=International Policy Digest  |date=4 April 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|Am\u00e9lie (soundtrack)}}\nThe soundtrack to ''Am\u00e9lie'' was composed by [[Yann Tiersen]].<ref>{{cite web | title=JEUNET, JEAN-PIERRE: FABULOUS DESTINY OF AM\u00c9LIE | url=http://www.urbancinefile.com.au/home/view.asp?a=5593&s=Interviews | publisher=Urban Cinefile  | date=13 December 2001 | accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Musical adaptation==\n{{main|Am\u00e9lie (musical)}}\n\nOn 23 August 2013, composer Dan Messe, one of the founders and members of the band [[Hem (band)|Hem]], confirmed speculation that he would be writing the score for a musical adaptation of ''Am\u00e9lie'', collaborating with [[Craig Lucas]] and [[Nathan Tysen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-23808207 |title=Amelie musical to be made for Broadway |publisher=BBC |date=23 August 2013 |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=23 August 2013, 9: 58 AM |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-207_162-57599847/amelie-becoming-a-broadway-musical/ |title=\"Amelie\" becoming a Broadway musical |publisher=CBS News |date=23 August 2013 |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref> Messe also confirmed he would be composing all original music for the show and not using the [[Yann Tiersen]] score.<ref name=\"broadway\">{{cite news| url= http://broadwaytour.net/amelie-set-to-be-adapted-for-broadway | work=Broadway Tour | title='Amelie' Set to be Adapted for Broadway | date=26 August 2013}}</ref> The [[Am\u00e9lie (musical)|musical adaptation]] premiered at the Berkeley Repertory Theater in August 2015.<ref>{{cite news|author=Robert Hurwitt|date=14 September 2015|title=Fanciful Film Floats Dreamily Onto the Stage with \"Am\u00e9lie\"|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|url=http://www.sfgate.com/performance/article/Am-lie-is-a-dream-of-a-musical-at-Berkeley-6500931.php|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> It opened on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in March 2017 and closed in May 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/hamilton-39-s-phillipa-soo-will-star-in-amelie-musical-on-broadway |title= Hamilton's Phillipa Soo Will Star in Am\u00e9lie Musical on Broadway |magazine=Playbill |date=17 June 2016 |first=Robert | last=Viagas|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> The production started its pre-Broadway engagement at the Ahmanson Theatre in Los Angeles in December 2016, with [[Phillipa Soo]] in the title role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centertheatregroup.org/tickets/ahmanson-theatre/2016-17/amelie-a-new-musical/|title=Am\u00e9lie, A New Musical|website=Center Theatre Group|access-date=15 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nJeunet distanced himself from the musical, saying he only sold the rights to raise funds for children's charity \"{{Interlanguage link multi|M\u00e9c\u00e9nat Chirurgie Cardiaque|fr}}\" (Cardiac Surgery Patronage).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/amelie-director-jean-pierre-jeunet-616611 |title='Amelie' Director Jean-Pierre Jeunet 'Disgusted' by Musical |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=28 August 2013 |accessdate=25 January 2014 |first=Rhonda |last=Richford}}</ref><!-- Article based on an interview France's RTL {{citation needed}} for original french language source too ideally -->\n\n==Home media==\n{{Anchor|Home media}}\nThe film has no overall worldwide distributor, but [[Blu-ray Disc]]s have been released in Canada and Australia. The first release occurred in Canada in September 2008 by TVA Films. This version did not contain any English subtitles and received criticisms regarding picture quality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Amelie-Blu-ray/1273/ |title=Amelie Blu-ray (Le Fabuleux Destin d'Am\u00e9lie Poulain) (2001) |publisher=Blu-ray.com |accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref> In November 2009, an Australian release occurred. This time the version contained English subtitles and features no region coding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Amelie-Blu-ray/7813/ |title=Amelie Blu-ray (Le Fabuleux Destin d'Am\u00e9lie Poulain) (2001) |publisher=Blu-ray.com |accessdate=28 April 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100414070910/http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Amelie-Blu-ray/7813/| archivedate= 14 April 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Momentum Pictures released a Blu-ray in the UK on 17 October 2011. The film is also available in HD on [[iTunes Store|iTunes]] and other digital download services.\n\n==Legacy==\nFor the 2007 television show ''[[Pushing Daisies]]'', a \"quirky fairy tale\", [[American Broadcasting Company]] (ABC) sought an ''Am\u00e9lie'' feel, with the same chords of \"whimsy and spirit and magic\". ''Pushing Daisies'' creator [[Bryan Fuller]] said ''Am\u00e9lie'' is his favorite film. \"All the things I love are represented in that movie\", he said. \"It's a movie that will make me cry based on kindness as opposed to sadness\". ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} review of ''Pushing Daisies'' reported \"the ''Am\u00e9lie'' influence on ''Pushing Daisies'' is everywhere\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Bill|last=Carter|title=A Touching Romance, if They Just Don't Touch|work=The New York Times |date=5 July 2007|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/05/arts/television/05dais.html}}</ref>\n\nA species of frog was named ''[[Cochranella]] amelie''. The scientist who named it said: \"[T]his new species of [[glass frog]] is for Am\u00e9lie, protagonist of the extraordinary movie ''Le Fabuleux Destin d'Am\u00e9lie Poulain''; a film where little details play an important role in the achievement of ''[[joie de vivre]]''; like the important role that glass frogs and all amphibians and reptiles play in the health of our planet\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2007f/zt01572p082.pdf |title=zt01572p082.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref> The species was described in the scientific journal ''Zootaxa''<ref>{{cite web|author=mp |url=http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/ |title=Zootaxa; a mega-journal for zoological taxonomists |publisher=Mapress.com |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref> in an article entitled \"An enigmatic new species of Glassfrog (Amphibia: Anura: Centrolenidae) from the Amazonian Andean slopes of Ecuador\".<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Mapress.com|title=An enigmatic new species of Glassfrog (Amphibia: Anura: Centrolenidae) from the Amazonian Andean slopes of Ecuador|url=http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2007f/z01485p041f.pdf|year=2007}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cinema of France]]\n* [[List of French language films]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.miramax.com/movie/amelie}}\n* {{IMDb title|0211915|Am\u00e9lie}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|amelie}}\n* {{mojo title|amelie|Am\u00e9lie}}\n* [http://www.hollywoodgothique.com/jeunet.html Jean-Pierre Jeunet discusses the film]\n\n{{Jean-Pierre Jeunet}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for ''Am\u00e9lie''\n|list =\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Foreign Language Film}}\n{{Crystal Globe}}\n{{European Film Award for Best Film}}\n{{European Film Award \u2013 People's Choice Award for Best European Film}}\n{{Goya Award for Best European Film}}\n{{Guldbagge Award Best Foreign Film}}\n{{Independent Spirit Award for Best International Film}}\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for Foreign Language Film of the Year}}\n{{Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best Film}}\n{{TIFF People's Choice Award}}\n}}\n{{French submission for Academy Awards}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amelie}}\n[[Category:2001 films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:German films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:French romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:German romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Best Film C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Film Lumi\u00e8res Award winners]]\n[[Category:European Film Awards winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Crystal Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jean-Pierre Jeunet]]\n[[Category:Films whose director won the Best Director C\u00e9sar Award]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Lumi\u00e8res Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Yann Tiersen]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1973]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1997]]\n[[Category:Films set in France]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Original Screenplay BAFTA Award]]\n[[Category:Films with live action and animation]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award for Best Foreign Film winners]]\n[[Category:Best Foreign Film Guldbagge Award winners]]\n[[Category:Magic realism films]]\n[[Category:Montmartre]]\n[[Category:Czech Lion Awards winners (films)]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Amelie||Am\u00e9lie (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|2001 film directed by Jean-Pierre Jeunet}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Am\u00e9lie\n| image          = Amelie poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = French theatrical poster\n| director       = [[Jean-Pierre Jeunet]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Jean-Marc Deschamps\n* Claudie Ossard\n}}\n| screenplay     = Guillaume Laurant\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Guillaume Laurant\n* Jean-Pierre Jeunet\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Audrey Tautou]]\n* [[Mathieu Kassovitz]]\n* [[Rufus (actor)|Rufus]]\n* [[Lorella Cravotta]]\n* [[Serge Merlin]]\n* [[Jamel Debbouze]]\n* [[Claire Maurier]]\n* [[Clotilde Mollet]]\n* [[Isabelle Nanty]]\n* [[Dominique Pinon]]\n* [[Artus de Penguern]]\n* [[Yolande Moreau]]\n* [[Urbain Cancelier]]\n* [[Maurice B\u00e9nichou]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Yann Tiersen]]\n| cinematography = [[Bruno Delbonnel]]\n| editing        = [[Herv\u00e9 Schneid]]\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Canal+]]\n* [[France 3 Cin\u00e9ma]]\n* [[UGC (cinema operator)|UGC]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[UGC-Fox Distribution]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=y|2001|04|25|France|2001|08|16|Germany}}\n| runtime        = 123 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 122:43--><ref>{{cite web|title=''AMELIE FROM MONTMARTRE (LE FABULEUX DESTIN D'AMELIE POULAIN)'' (15)|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/amelie-montmartre-le-fabuleux-destin-damelie-poulain-2001|work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]|date=17 July 2001|accessdate=13 April 2013}}</ref>\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* France\n* Germany\n}}\n| language       = French\n| budget         = $10&nbsp;million<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n| gross          = $174.2&nbsp;million<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web |url= http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Fabuleux-destin-d-Amelie-Poulain-Le#tab=summary |title=Am\u00e9lie (2001) | work = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |publisher= [[IMDb]]  |accessdate=25 September 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Am\u00e9lie''''' (also known as '''''Le Fabuleux Destin d'Am\u00e9lie Poulain'''''; {{IPA-fr|l\u0259 fabyl\u00f8 dest\u025b\u0303 d\u203fameli pul\u025b\u0303}}; {{lang-en|The Fabulous Destiny of Am\u00e9lie Poulain|italic=yes}}) is a 2001 French [[romantic comedy]] film directed by [[Jean-Pierre Jeunet]]. Written by Jeunet with Guillaume Laurant, the film is a whimsical depiction of contemporary Parisian life, set in [[Montmartre]]. It tells the story of a shy waitress, played by [[Audrey Tautou]], who decides to change the lives of those around her for the better while struggling with her own isolation. The film was a [[International co-production|co-production]] between companies in [[Cinema of France|France]] and [[Cinema of Germany|Germany]]. Taking in over $33&nbsp;million in a limited theatrical release, it is to date the highest-grossing French-language film released in the United States, and one of the biggest international successes for a French movie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=foreign.htm&sort=gross&order=DESC&p=.htm |title=Foreign Language Movies at the Box Office |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe film received critical acclaim and was a major box office success. ''Am\u00e9lie'' won [[European Film Award for Best Film|Best Film]] at the [[European Film Awards]]; it also won four [[C\u00e9sar Award]]s in 2002 (including [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film|Best Film]] and [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Director|Best Director]]), two [[55th British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Awards]] (including [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]), and was nominated for five [[Academy Awards]].\n\n==Plot==\n[[File:Paris - Caf\u00e9 des 2 Moulins - 2004.jpg|thumb|left|Am\u00e9lie works at the [[Caf\u00e9 des 2 Moulins]] in Montmartre]]\n\nAm\u00e9lie Poulain is born in June 1974 and brought up by eccentric parents who \u2013 incorrectly believing that she has a heart defect \u2013 decide to home-school her. To cope with her loneliness, Am\u00e9lie develops an active imagination and a mischievous personality. When Am\u00e9lie is six, her mother, Amandine, is killed when a suicidal Canadian tourist jumps from the roof of [[Notre-Dame de Paris]] and lands on her. As a result, her father Rapha\u00ebl ([[Rufus (actor)|Rufus]]) withdraws more and more from society. Am\u00e9lie leaves home at the age of 18 and becomes a waitress at the [[Caf\u00e9 des 2 Moulins]] in [[Montmartre]], which is staffed and frequented by a collection of eccentrics. She is single and lets her imagination roam freely, finding contentment in simple pleasures like dipping her hand into grain sacks and cracking [[cr\u00e8me br\u00fbl\u00e9e]] with a spoon.\n\nOn 31 August 1997, startled by the news of the [[death of Diana, Princess of Wales]], Am\u00e9lie drops a plastic perfume-stopper, which dislodges a wall tile and accidentally reveals an old metal box of childhood memorabilia hidden by a boy who lived in her apartment decades earlier. Am\u00e9lie resolves to track down the boy and return the box to him. She promises herself that if it makes him happy, she will devote her life to bringing happiness to others.\n\nAfter asking the apartment's concierge and several old tenants about the boy's identity, Am\u00e9lie meets her reclusive neighbour, Raymond Dufayel, an artist with [[Osteogenesis imperfecta|brittle bone disease]] who repaints [[Pierre-Auguste Renoir|Renoir]]'''s [[Luncheon of the Boating Party]]'' every year. He recalls the boy's name as \"Bretodeau\". Am\u00e9lie quickly finds the man, Dominique Bretodeau, and surreptitiously gives him the box. Moved to tears by the discovery and the memories it holds, Bretodeau resolves to reconcile with his estranged daughter and the grandson he has never met. Am\u00e9lie happily embarks on her new mission.\n\nAm\u00e9lie secretly executes complex schemes that affect the lives of those around her. She escorts a blind man to the M\u00e9tro station, giving him a rich description of the street scenes he passes. She persuades her father to follow his dream of touring the world by stealing his [[garden gnome]] and having a flight attendant friend [[airmail]] pictures of it [[Travelling gnome prank|posing with landmarks from all over the world]]. She starts a romance between her hypochondriacal co-worker Georgette and Joseph, one of the customers in the bar. She convinces Madeleine Wallace, the concierge of her block of flats, that the husband who abandoned her had sent her a final conciliatory love letter just before his accidental death years before. She [[Gaslighting|gaslights]] Collignon, the nasty greengrocer. Mentally exhausted, Collignon no longer abuses his meek but good-natured assistant Lucien. A delighted Lucien takes charge at the grocery stand.\n\nMr. Dufayel, having observed Am\u00e9lie, begins a conversation with her about his painting. Although he has copied the same painting 20 times, he has never quite captured the look of the girl drinking a glass of water. They discuss the meaning of this character, and over several conversations, Am\u00e9lie begins projecting her loneliness onto the image. Dufayel recognizes this and uses the girl in the painting to push Am\u00e9lie to examine her attraction to a quirky young man, Nino Quincampoix, who collects the discarded photographs of strangers from passport photo booths. When Am\u00e9lie bumps into Nino a second time, she realizes she is falling in love with him. He accidentally drops a photo album in the street. Am\u00e9lie retrieves it.\n\nAm\u00e9lie plays a cat-and-mouse game with Nino around Paris before returning his treasured album anonymously. After arranging a meeting at the 2 Moulins, Am\u00e9lie panics and tries to deny her identity. Her co-worker, Gina ([[Clotilde Mollet]]), concerned for Am\u00e9lie's well-being, screens Nino for her; Joseph's comment about this misleads Am\u00e9lie to believe she has lost Nino to Gina. It takes Dufayel's insight to give her the courage to pursue Nino, resulting in a romantic night together and the beginning of a relationship. Am\u00e9lie finally finds happiness for herself.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Audrey Tautou]] as Am\u00e9lie Poulain \n** Flora Guiet as young Am\u00e9lie\n* [[Mathieu Kassovitz]] as Nino Quincampoix\n** Amaury Babault as young Nino\n* [[Rufus (actor)|Rufus]] as Rapha\u00ebl Poulain, Am\u00e9lie's father\n* [[Serge Merlin]] as Raymond Dufayel, \"The Glass Man\"\n* [[Lorella Cravotta]] as Amandine Poulain, Am\u00e9lie's mother\n* [[Clotilde Mollet]] as Gina, a fellow waitress\n* [[Claire Maurier]] as Suzanne, the owner of Caf\u00e9 des Deux Moulins\n* [[Isabelle Nanty]] as Georgette, the resident hypochondriac\n* [[Dominique Pinon]] as Joseph\n* [[Artus de Penguern]] as Hipolito, the writer\n* [[Yolande Moreau]] as Madeleine Wallace (Wells, in English subtitled version)\n* [[Urbain Cancelier]] as Collignon, the grocer\n* [[Jamel Debbouze]] as Lucien, the grocer's assistant\n* [[Maurice B\u00e9nichou]] as Dominique Bretodeau\n** Kevin Fernandes as young Dominique\n* [[Michel Robin]] as Mr. Collignon\n* [[Andr\u00e9e Damant]] as Mrs. Collignon\n* [[Claude Perron]] as Eva, Nino's colleague\n* [[Armelle]] as Philom\u00e8ne, air hostess\n* [[Ticky Holgado]] as Man in a photo\n* [[Fabienne Chaudat]] as The woman in a coma\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:20051018\u00c9picerie d'Am\u00e9lie Poulain 2.jpg|thumb|Au March\u00e9 de la Butte, Rue des Trois Fr\u00e8res, Paris, used as the location of Monsieur Collignon's shop]]\n\nIn his [[Audio commentary|DVD commentary]], Jeunet explains that he originally wrote the role of Am\u00e9lie for the English actress [[Emily Watson]]. In that first draft, Am\u00e9lie's father was an Englishman living in London. However, Watson's French was not strong, and when she became unavailable to shoot the film, owing to a conflict with the filming of ''[[Gosford Park]]'', Jeunet rewrote the screenplay for a French actress. [[Audrey Tautou]] was the first actress he auditioned having seen her on the poster for the 1999 film ''[[Venus Beauty Institute]]''.\n\nThe movie was filmed mainly in Paris. The [[Caf\u00e9 des 2 Moulins]] (15 Rue Lepic, Montmartre, Paris) where Am\u00e9lie works is a real place.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Am\u00e9lie: filming locations |work=Movieloci.com |date=23 July 2012 |url=http://www.movieloci.com/281-Amelie-from-Montmartre?snapshot=2794}}</ref>\n\nThe filmmakers made use of [[computer-generated imagery]] (including [[computer animation]]),<ref>{{cite news|last=Arnold|first=William|date=8 November 2001|title=Inspired 'Am\u00e9lie' blends solid comedy with cutting-edge special effects|url=https://www.seattlepi.com/ae/movies/article/Inspired-Amelie-blends-solid-comedy-with-1071154.php|newspaper=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|access-date=8 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/18111/looking-back-at-jean-pierre-jeunets-amelie|title=Looking back at Jean Pierre-Jeunet's Amelie|last=Bond|first=Zoe|date=29 September 2011|publisher=Den of Geek|access-date=8 June 2019}}</ref> and a [[digital intermediate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/ac2005_article/VR1117915901?nav=lenser&categoryid=1804|title=Color schemes: Lensers view new post-prod'n process as an integral tool in their paint box|work=Variety|date=6 January 2005|accessdate=8 June 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060106232403/http://www.variety.com/ac2005_article/VR1117915901?nav=lenser&categoryid=1804|archivedate=6 January 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> The studio scenes were filmed in the Coloneum Studio in [[Cologne]] (Germany). The film shares many of the themes in the plot with second half of the 1994 film ''[[Chungking Express]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediacircus.net/amelie.html |title=Amelie Movie Review by Anthony Leong from |publisher=MediaCircus.net |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dickerson |first=Jeff |url=http://www.michigandaily.com/content/audrey-tautou-and-french-film-amelie-are-pure-movie-magic |title=Audrey Tautou and French film `Amelie' are pure movie magic |newspaper=[[The Michigan Daily]] |date=10 April 2002 |accessdate=9 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released in France, Belgium, and [[Romandy|French-speaking western Switzerland]] in April 2001, with subsequent screenings at various film festivals followed by releases around the world. It received [[limited release]]s in North America, the United Kingdom, and [[Australasia]] later in 2001.\n\n[[Cannes Film Festival]] selector Gilles Jacob described ''Am\u00e9lie'' as \"uninteresting\", and therefore it was not screened at the festival, although the version he viewed was an early cut without music. The absence of ''Am\u00e9lie'' at the festival caused something of a controversy because of the warm welcome by the French media and audience in contrast with the reaction of the selector.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tobias |first=Scott |url=http://www.avclub.com/content/node/22708 |title=Jean-Pierre Jeunet |newspaper=The A.V. Club |accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref> David Martin-Jones, in an article in ''[[Senses of Cinema]]'', stated that the film \"[wears] its national [French] identity on its sleeve\" and that this attracted both audiences of mainstream movies and those of [[arthouse]] ones.<ref name=\"Martin-Jones\">{{cite web |title=Review: 'Colombiana: Europa Corp and the Ambiguous Geopolitics of the Action Movie'|work=[[Senses of Cinema]]|url=http://sensesofcinema.com/2012/feature-articles/colombiana-europa-corp-and-the-ambiguous-geopolitics-of-the-action-movie/|first=David |last=Martin-Jones |date= 1 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an 89% approval rating, based on 178 reviews, with an average rating of 8.1/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"The feel-good ''Am\u00e9lie'' is a lively, fanciful charmer, showcasing Audrey Tautou as its delightful heroine\".<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/amelie/|title=Am\u00e9lie (2001)|accessdate=10 April 2018|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a score of 69 out of 100, based on 31 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/amelie |title=Am\u00e9lie Reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]  |date=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlan Morrison from [[Empire (film magazine)|''Empire'' Online]] gave ''Am\u00e9lie'' five stars and called it \"one of the year's best, with crossover potential along the lines of ''[[Cyrano de Bergerac (1990 film)|Cyrano De Bergerac]]'' and ''[[Il Postino]]''. Given its quirky heart, it might well surpass them all\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/ReviewComplete.asp?FID=7284 |title=Empire's Amelie Movie Review |work=Empire (film magazine) |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref>                                                                    Blogger Sarmad Iqbal from [[International Policy Digest]] commented in his review that \u201cWhat makes this film special is indeed the innocence of the leading protagonist intertwined with her frequent retreats from it.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://intpolicydigest.org/2020/04/04/seven-binge-worthy-french-films-to-get-you-through-self-isolation/ |title=Seven Binge Worthy French Films to Get You Through Self-Isolation |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nPaul Tatara of [[CNN]] praised ''Am\u00e9lie''{{'}}s playful nature. In his review, he wrote, \"Its whimsical, free-ranging nature is often enchanting; the first hour, in particular, is brimming with amiable, sardonic laughs\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/SHOWBIZ/Movies/11/07/review.amelie/index.html | publisher=[[CNN]] | title=Review: 'Amelie' is imaginative | date=7 November 2001}}</ref>\n\nThe film was attacked by critic Serge Kaganski of ''[[Les Inrockuptibles]]'' for an unrealistic and picturesque vision of a bygone French society with few [[Minority group|ethnic minorities]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmlinc.com/film-comment/article/the-amelie-effect |title=The Am\u00e9lie Effect |publisher=Filmlinc.com |accessdate=21 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323105658/http://www.filmlinc.com/film-comment/article/the-amelie-effect |archivedate=23 March 2012 }}</ref> Jeunet dismissed the criticism by pointing out that the photo collection contains pictures of people from numerous ethnic backgrounds, and that [[Jamel Debbouze]], who plays Lucien, is of Moroccan descent.\n\n===Awards and nominations=== <!-- fix reference in lead section if this section is renamed -->\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"5\"| [[Academy Awards]]<ref name=\"Oscars2002\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/74th-winners.html |title=The 74th Academy Awards (2002) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=19 November 2011|publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences}}</ref>\n| [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n| [[Jean-Pierre Jeunet]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]\n| Guillaume Laurant and Jean-Pierre Jeunet\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| [[Bruno Delbonnel]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]]\n| [[Aline Bonetto]] and [[Marie-Laure Valla]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Academy Award for Best Sound Mixing|Best Sound Mixing]]\n| [[Vincent Arnardi]], [[Guillaume Leriche]], [[Jean Umansky]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"9\"| [[British Academy Film Awards]]\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Direction]]\n| Jean-Pierre Jeunet \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|Best Actress in a Leading Role]]\n| [[Audrey Tautou]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]]\n| Guillaume Laurant and Jean-Pierre Jeunet\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| Bruno Delbonnel\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]]\n| Aline Bonetto\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n| [[Herv\u00e9 Schneid]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Music|Best Film Music]]\n| [[Yann Tiersen]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Not in the English Language|Best Film Not in the English Language]]\n| \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"12\"| [[C\u00e9sar Award]]s\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| Jean-Pierre Jeunet \n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| Audrey Tautou\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]]\n| [[Jamel Debbouze]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Rufus (actor)|Rufus]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n| [[Isabelle Nanty]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Writing|Best Writing]]\n| Guillaume Laurant and Jean-Pierre Jeunet\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]]\n| Bruno Delbonnel\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Production Design|Best Production Design]]\n| Aline Bonetto\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Costume Design|Best Costume Design]]\n| Madeline Fontaine\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]\n| Herv\u00e9 Schneid \n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Music|Best Music]]\n| Yann Tiersen\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"4\"| [[European Film Awards]]\n| [[European Film Award for Best Film|Best Film]]\n|rowspan=2| Jean-Pierre Jeunet\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[European Film Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[European Film Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| Audrey Tautou\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[European Film Award for Best Cinematographer|Best Cinematography]]\n| Bruno Delbonnel\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[French Syndicate of Cinema Critics]]\n| Best French Film\n|\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Golden Globe Award]]s\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film|Best Foreign Language Film]]\n|rowspan=2| Jean-Pierre Jeunet\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Karlovy Vary International Film Festival]]\n| [[Crystal Globe]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Toronto International Film Festival]]\n| [[Toronto International Film Festival People's Choice Award|People's Choice Award]]\n| \n| {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\nThe film was selected by ''[[The New York Times]]'' as one of \"The Best 1,000 Movies Ever Made\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/ref/movies/1000best.html | work=The New York Times | title=The Best 1,000 Movies Ever Made | date=29 April 2003 | accessdate=23 April 2010}}</ref> The film placed No. 2 in ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' magazine's \"The 100 Best Films of World Cinema\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Green |first1=Willow |title=The 100 Best Films Of World Cinema |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/100-greatest-world-cinema-films/ |website=Empire (film magazine) |accessdate=26 July 2019 |date=11 June 2010}}</ref> ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' magazine ranked it second on its list of the 50 Best Movies of the Decade (2000\u20132009).<ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Best Movies of the Decade (2000\u20132009)|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2009/11/50-best-movies-of-the-decade-2000-2009.html|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste Magazine]]|accessdate=14 December 2011|date=3 November 2009}}</ref> In August of that same year, ''[[BBC]] Magazine'' conducted a poll on the 21st century's 100 greatest films so far, with ''Am\u00e9lie'' ranking at number 87.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC Culture \u2013 The 21st Century's 100 greatest films|work=BBC Magazine|url=http://www.bbc.com/culture/story/20160819-the-21st-centurys-100-greatest-films|date=23 August 2016|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' named the film poster one of the best on its list of the top 25 film posters in the past 25 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20207076_20207387_20207597,00.html |title=Movies: 25 New Classic Posters |work=Entertainment Weekly  |date=27 June 2008 |accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref> It also named Am\u00e9lie setting up a wild goose chase for her beloved Nino all through Paris as No. 9 on its list of top 25 Romantic Gestures.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ew.com/gallery/25-most-romantic-gestures-film-0/?slide=341112#341112 |title=New Classics: Romantic Gestures |work=Entertainment Weekly  |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref> In 2010, an online public poll by the ''[[American Cinematographer]]'' \u2013 the house journal of the [[American Society of Cinematographers]] \u2013 named ''Am\u00e9lie'' the best shot film of the decade.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.movieline.com/2010/06/was-amelie-really-the-best-shot-film-of-the-last-decade.php |title=Was Am\u00e9lie Really the Best-Shot Film of the Last Decade? |publisher=movieline.com |date=29 June 2010 |accessdate=5 June 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701041512/http://www.movieline.com/2010/06/was-amelie-really-the-best-shot-film-of-the-last-decade.php |archivedate=1 July 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n''Amelie'' is rated 37 among the 50 Greatest Romantic Comedies of All Time by [[RollingStone]] Magazine<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-lists/50-greatest-romantic-comedies-of-all-time-790068/amelie-2001-792272/ |title=50 Greatest Romantic Comedies of All Time |work=Rolling Stone  |date=14 February 2019 |accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>                             ''Amelie'' is included  among the Seven Binge Worthy French Films to Get Through Self-Isolation by Sarmad Iqbal of [[International Policy Digest]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://intpolicydigest.org/2020/04/04/seven-binge-worthy-french-films-to-get-you-through-self-isolation/ |title= Seven Binge Worthy French Films to Get You Through Self-Isolation|work=International Policy Digest  |date=4 April 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|Am\u00e9lie (soundtrack)}}\nThe soundtrack to ''Am\u00e9lie'' was composed by [[Yann Tiersen]].<ref>{{cite web | title=JEUNET, JEAN-PIERRE: FABULOUS DESTINY OF AM\u00c9LIE | url=http://www.urbancinefile.com.au/home/view.asp?a=5593&s=Interviews | publisher=Urban Cinefile  | date=13 December 2001 | accessdate=5 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Musical adaptation==\n{{main|Am\u00e9lie (musical)}}\n\nOn 23 August 2013, composer Dan Messe, one of the founders and members of the band [[Hem (band)|Hem]], confirmed speculation that he would be writing the score for a musical adaptation of ''Am\u00e9lie'', collaborating with [[Craig Lucas]] and [[Nathan Tysen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-23808207 |title=Amelie musical to be made for Broadway |publisher=BBC |date=23 August 2013 |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=23 August 2013, 9: 58 AM |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-207_162-57599847/amelie-becoming-a-broadway-musical/ |title=\"Amelie\" becoming a Broadway musical |publisher=CBS News |date=23 August 2013 |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref> Messe also confirmed he would be composing all original music for the show and not using the [[Yann Tiersen]] score.<ref name=\"broadway\">{{cite news| url= http://broadwaytour.net/amelie-set-to-be-adapted-for-broadway | work=Broadway Tour | title='Amelie' Set to be Adapted for Broadway | date=26 August 2013}}</ref> The [[Am\u00e9lie (musical)|musical adaptation]] premiered at the Berkeley Repertory Theater in August 2015.<ref>{{cite news|author=Robert Hurwitt|date=14 September 2015|title=Fanciful Film Floats Dreamily Onto the Stage with \"Am\u00e9lie\"|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|url=http://www.sfgate.com/performance/article/Am-lie-is-a-dream-of-a-musical-at-Berkeley-6500931.php|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> It opened on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in March 2017 and closed in May 2017.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/hamilton-39-s-phillipa-soo-will-star-in-amelie-musical-on-broadway |title= Hamilton's Phillipa Soo Will Star in Am\u00e9lie Musical on Broadway |magazine=Playbill |date=17 June 2016 |first=Robert | last=Viagas|accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> The production started its pre-Broadway engagement at the Ahmanson Theatre in Los Angeles in December 2016, with [[Phillipa Soo]] in the title role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.centertheatregroup.org/tickets/ahmanson-theatre/2016-17/amelie-a-new-musical/|title=Am\u00e9lie, A New Musical|website=Center Theatre Group|access-date=15 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nJeunet distanced himself from the musical, saying he only sold the rights to raise funds for children's charity \"{{Interlanguage link multi|M\u00e9c\u00e9nat Chirurgie Cardiaque|fr}}\" (Cardiac Surgery Patronage).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/amelie-director-jean-pierre-jeunet-616611 |title='Amelie' Director Jean-Pierre Jeunet 'Disgusted' by Musical |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=28 August 2013 |accessdate=25 January 2014 |first=Rhonda |last=Richford}}</ref><!-- Article based on an interview France's RTL {{citation needed}} for original french language source too ideally -->\n\n==Home media==\n{{Anchor|Home media}}\nThe film has no overall worldwide distributor, but [[Blu-ray Disc]]s have been released in Canada and Australia. The first release occurred in Canada in September 2008 by TVA Films. This version did not contain any English subtitles and received criticisms regarding picture quality.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Amelie-Blu-ray/1273/ |title=Amelie Blu-ray (Le Fabuleux Destin d'Am\u00e9lie Poulain) (2001) |publisher=Blu-ray.com |accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref> In November 2009, an Australian release occurred. This time the version contained English subtitles and features no region coding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Amelie-Blu-ray/7813/ |title=Amelie Blu-ray (Le Fabuleux Destin d'Am\u00e9lie Poulain) (2001) |publisher=Blu-ray.com |accessdate=28 April 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100414070910/http://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Amelie-Blu-ray/7813/| archivedate= 14 April 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> Momentum Pictures released a Blu-ray in the UK on 17 October 2011. The film is also available in HD on [[iTunes Store|iTunes]] and other digital download services.\n\n==Legacy==\nFor the 2007 television show ''[[Pushing Daisies]]'', a \"quirky fairy tale\", [[American Broadcasting Company]] (ABC) sought an ''Am\u00e9lie'' feel, with the same chords of \"whimsy and spirit and magic\". ''Pushing Daisies'' creator [[Bryan Fuller]] said ''Am\u00e9lie'' is his favorite film. \"All the things I love are represented in that movie\", he said. \"It's a movie that will make me cry based on kindness as opposed to sadness\". ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} review of ''Pushing Daisies'' reported \"the ''Am\u00e9lie'' influence on ''Pushing Daisies'' is everywhere\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Bill|last=Carter|title=A Touching Romance, if They Just Don't Touch|work=The New York Times |date=5 July 2007|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/05/arts/television/05dais.html}}</ref>\n\nA species of frog was named ''[[Cochranella]] amelie''. The scientist who named it said: \"[T]his new species of [[glass frog]] is for Am\u00e9lie, protagonist of the extraordinary movie ''Le Fabuleux Destin d'Am\u00e9lie Poulain''; a film where little details play an important role in the achievement of ''[[joie de vivre]]''; like the important role that glass frogs and all amphibians and reptiles play in the health of our planet\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2007f/zt01572p082.pdf |title=zt01572p082.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref> The species was described in the scientific journal ''Zootaxa''<ref>{{cite web|author=mp |url=http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/ |title=Zootaxa; a mega-journal for zoological taxonomists |publisher=Mapress.com |accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref> in an article entitled \"An enigmatic new species of Glassfrog (Amphibia: Anura: Centrolenidae) from the Amazonian Andean slopes of Ecuador\".<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Mapress.com|title=An enigmatic new species of Glassfrog (Amphibia: Anura: Centrolenidae) from the Amazonian Andean slopes of Ecuador|url=http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2007f/z01485p041f.pdf|year=2007}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cinema of France]]\n* [[List of French language films]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.miramax.com/movie/amelie}}\n* {{IMDb title|0211915|Am\u00e9lie}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|amelie}}\n* {{mojo title|amelie|Am\u00e9lie}}\n* [http://www.hollywoodgothique.com/jeunet.html Jean-Pierre Jeunet discusses the film]\n\n{{Jean-Pierre Jeunet}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for ''Am\u00e9lie''\n|list =\n{{C\u00e9sar Award for Best Film}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Foreign Language Film}}\n{{Crystal Globe}}\n{{European Film Award for Best Film}}\n{{European Film Award \u2013 People's Choice Award for Best European Film}}\n{{Goya Award for Best European Film}}\n{{Guldbagge Award Best Foreign Film}}\n{{Independent Spirit Award for Best International Film}}\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for Foreign Language Film of the Year}}\n{{Lumi\u00e8res Award for Best Film}}\n{{TIFF People's Choice Award}}\n}}\n{{French submission for Academy Awards}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amelie}}\n[[Category:2001 films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:German films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:French romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:German romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Best Film C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Film Lumi\u00e8res Award winners]]\n[[Category:European Film Awards winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Crystal Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jean-Pierre Jeunet]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Lumi\u00e8res Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Yann Tiersen]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1973]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1997]]\n[[Category:Films set in France]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Original Screenplay BAFTA Award]]\n[[Category:Films with live action and animation]]\n[[Category:Independent Spirit Award for Best Foreign Film winners]]\n[[Category:Best Foreign Film Guldbagge Award winners]]\n[[Category:Magic realism films]]\n[[Category:Montmartre]]\n[[Category:Czech Lion Awards winners (films)]]\n", "name_user": "Diopic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:addCategory:Films whose director won the Best Director C\u00e9sar Award", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Am%C3%A9lie"}
{"title_page": "Super Impassioned Net Generation", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Super Impassioned Net Generation (SING)\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = SING_3rd_Anniversary.jpg\n| image_size       = 350\n| landscape        = yes\n| alt              = SING 3rd Anniversary on Aug 27, 2018\n| caption          = SING 3rd Anniversary on Aug 27, 2018\n| alias            = SING Girls\n| origin           = [[China]]\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[C-pop]]|[[Mandopop]]|[[Dance music]]|[[Electro House]]}}\n| years_active     = 2015\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[KuGou]]|Qigu Culture|JSJ International Entertainment}}\n| associated_acts  = [[Rocket Girls (band)|Rocket Girls]]\n| website          = {{url|http://sing.fanxing.kugou.com/}}\n| current_members  = * Qin Yu (Sophie)\n* Bian Li (Jessica)\n* Lin Hui (Haha)\n* [[Lai Meiyun]] (Sunny)\n* Jiang Shen (Debbie)\n* Xu Shiyin (Valentina)\n* Chen Li (Pink)\n* Wu Yao (Miko)\n| former_members   = * Lin Jinyi (Magical)\n* Cai Sha (SaSa)\n* Wang Wenjie (Candy)\n* Chen Wenrou (Ruby)\n* Gong Tianying (Lorinda)|\n}}\n\n'''SING''', also known as '''Super Impassioned Net Generation''' ({{zh|s=SING\u5973\u56e2|t=SING\u5973\u5718|p=/s\u026a\u014b/ n\u01da tu\u00e1n|l=Sing Girls' Group}}) is a Chinese [[girl group]] formed by [[KuGou|KuGou Music]] in 2015 with 10 members, selected from different regions of [[China]]. The current line-up is composed of eight members, and they primarily produce [[electronic dance music]] inspired by traditional Chinese music.\n\n==History==\n===2015: Formation and debut===\nSING debuted in 2015 with ten members on August 10, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.qq.com/a/20150811/037962.htm|title=S.I.N.G Debut (S.I.N.G\u5973\u5b50\u5076\u50cf\u56e2\u4f53\u51fa\u9053 \u6d3b\u529b\u7efd\u653e\u9752\u6625\u544a\u767d)|work=[[Tencent]] News|date=August 11, 2015|language=Chinese}}</ref> Given the limitations on budget, the group did not rely on income from concert tickets, instead gaining primary revenues from royalty, licensing fees, and selling merchandise.<ref name=\"sina_news\">{{cite web|url=http://k.sina.com.cn/article_6283799853_1768b2d2d001007dp1.html|title=Trying to survive as an idol group (101\u5973\u56e2\u56fe\u9274\u2460\uff1a\u7535\u5b50\u56fd\u98ce\u5973\u56e2\u6c42\u751f\u8bb0)|work=[[Sina Corp|Sina News]]|date=June 3, 2018|language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\n===2016: Line-up changes===\nFour members suspended their activities in 2016, and three new members were added to the group.<ref name=\"sina_news\" />\n\n===2017: Change in sound and breakthrough===\nIn September, SING released the single \"Moonlight Thoughts\" ({{zh|s=\u5bc4\u660e\u6708|p=J\u00ec m\u00edngyu\u00e8}}), their first ever Chinese-style electronic dance song. The single helped the group gain popularity and momentum in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yule.sohu.com/20170928/n514911808.shtml|title=The Chinese style EDM (SING\u5973\u56e2\u300a\u5bc4\u660e\u6708\u300b\u53d1\u5e03 \u534e\u8bed\"\u7535\u5b50\u56fd\u98ce\"\u7b2c\u4e00\u67aa)|work=[[Sohu]]|date=September 28, 2017|language=Chinese}}</ref> In December, the group held a [[Christmas]] live concert named ''Part of Me''. Following the concert, Lin Jinyi suspended her activities due to health concerns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.ifeng.com/a/20171226/43016520_0.shtml|title=Chinese EDM Group SING live concert (\u7535\u5b50\u56fd\u98ce\u5973\u56e2SING\u5973\u56e2\u516c\u6f14 \u5f15\u7c89\u4e1d\u72c2\u6253CALL)|work=[[Phoenix Television]]|date=December 26, 2018|language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\nIn November, the group released their first international album ''SING'' on [[iTunes]] and [[Spotify]].\n\n===2018-2019: Continued success===\n\nThree members of SING participated in the reality idol competition [[Produce 101 (Chinese TV series)|''Produce 101'']] in March 2018. Jiang Shen and Xu Shiyin finished at 23rd and 75th place, respectively; [[Lai Meiyun]] made the final line up at 6th place and successfully debuted as a member of [[Rocket Girls (band)|Rocket Girls]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1108147.shtml|title=Chinese idol competition reality show 'Produce 101' reveals members of China's newest girl band Rocket Girls|work=[[Global Times]]|date=June 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSING performed on the 2nd International Youth Conference in [[Shenzhen]] on August 12.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://passport.weibo.com/visitor/visitor?entry=miniblog&a=enter&url=https%3A%2F%2Fweibo.com%2F5281360151%2FGuliFwPfm&domain=.weibo.com&ua=php-sso_sdk_client-0.6.28&_rand=1550245267.1133|title=The 2nd International Youth Conference|website=passport.weibo.com}}</ref> Sophie presented a speech titled \"[https://www.bilibili.com/video/av29380820 Integration of Youth Culture and Traditional Culture from the Perspective of Electronic Chinese Style Music]\" to introduce insights on young people\u2019s inheritance and innovation in traditional Chinese culture based on her personal experience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bilibili.com/read/cv957801/|title=Integration of Youth Culture and Traditional Culture from the Perspective of Electronic Chinese Style Music|last=SING\u5973\u56e2|website=www.bilibili.com}}</ref>\n\nSING joined the TV Show competition \"''Wo Yao Shang Chun Wan''\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u6211\u8981\u4e0a\u6625\u665a)  with \"Moonlight Thoughts\" on December 29, 2018. This TV show competition selected the performance for the CCTV Spring Festival Event. SING lost but advanced to the final through fan voting. ([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IjAkmXWK8U0&t=34s youtube] )<ref>{{Citation|last=CCTV\u6625\u665a|title=[2018\u6211\u8981\u4e0a\u6625\u665a] \u56fd\u98ce\u7f8e\u5c11\u5973\uff01\u7535\u97f3\u5973\u56e2SING\u300a\u5bc4\u660e\u6708\u300b\u5f15\u53d1\u5168\u7403\u6a21\u4eff \u98de\u82b1\u4ee4\u4e5f\u96be\u4e0d\u5012 \u8fd9\u662f\u4e2a\u6709\u6587\u5316\u7684\u56e2\uff01 {{!}} CCTV\u6625\u665a|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IjAkmXWK8U0&t=34s|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\nXu Shiyin released her first solo \"Bai Yi Shao Nian\" ([[Simplified chinese|Simplified Chinese]]: \u767d\u8863\u5c11\u5e74) on March 14 and its accompanying music video on June 26.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ent.tom.com/201807/1907256781.html|title=SING\u5973\u56e2\u8bb8\u8bd7\u8335\u539f\u521b\u66f2\u300a\u767d\u8863\u5c11\u5e74\u300bPV\u4e0a\u7ebf_TOM\u5a31\u4e50|website=ent.tom.com}}</ref> The song was used as the ending theme for the drama \"I Will Never Let You Go\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u5c0f\u5973\u82b1\u4e0d\u5f03) which aired on January 8, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://culture.people.com.cn/n1/2019/0108/c1013-30510106.html|title=SING\u5973\u56e2\u8bb8\u8bd7\u8335\u732e\u5531\u300a\u5c0f\u5973\u82b1\u4e0d\u5f03\u300b\u5531\u4f5c\u53cc\u7edd--\u6587\u5316--\u4eba\u6c11\u7f51|website=culture.people.com.cn}}</ref>\n\nThe variety show ''SING HOME'' began airing in 2019, with each episode having a different theme and featuring content such as playing games, team discussions, and interacting with fans. \n\nDebbie released her first solo song \"Mermaid\" on January 4, and its music video on January 21. Debbie explained that she chose the title because she hoped her first solo would attract people to her, like the singing of a mermaid.\n\nSING performed the song \"Ru Meng Ling\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u5982\u68a6\u4ee4) in the final of \"''Wo Yao Shang Chun Wan''\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u6211\u8981\u4e0a\u6625\u665a) in January 26. They lost the judges vote 0-5 to their competitor. ([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UuVQA41DOtw youtube]) SING, [[Han Xue (actress)|Han Xue]], and [[Wu Mochou]] performed the song \"''Hui Jia Guo Nian La''\"([[simplified chinese]]: \u56de\u5bb6\u8fc7\u5e74\u5566) on the CCTV Internet Spring Festival Event in January 28.([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yIsXldBz7Mg youtube]) SING, [[Han Xue (actress)|Han Xue]], and Oscar Qian performed the song \"''Nian Ye Fan''\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u5e74\u591c\u996d)  for the Hunan TV Spring Festival Event on January 29.([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ppxNwlxGr4w youtube])\nSING performed the song \"Huan Le Zhong Guo Nian\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u6b22\u4e50\u4e2d\u56fd\u5e74)  for the Jiangxi TV Spring Festival Event on February 3.([https://m.weibo.cn/status/4335699329270759 Weibo]) SING performed the song \"Tuan Tuan Yuan Yuan\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u56e2\u56e2\u5706\u5706) for the CCTV Spring Festival Event Countdown on February 4.([https://www.bilibili.com/video/av42648777?share_medium=android&share_source=copy_link&bbid=XY329E639E3297D3625EBC6A30098B602C166&ts=1549306819956 bilibili]) SING performed the song \"Ru Meng Ling\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u5982\u68a6\u4ee4)  and \"Qian Nian\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u5343\u5e74) for the GuangDong TV Spring Festival on February 4.([https://www.bilibili.com/video/av43408217 bilibili]) Their song \"Tuan Tuan Yuan Yuan\" ([[simplified Chinese]]: \u56e2\u56e2\u5706\u5706) was used as the background music of \"The Reunion\" on the 7th Hong Kong Lunar New Year Firework Show on February 6.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hk01.com/\u89aa\u5b50/290200/\u8cc0\u6b72\u7159\u82b1-\u521d\u4e8c\u7159\u82b1\u532f\u6f14\u6709\u8c6c\u9f3b\u5716\u6848-\u56db\u500b\u7747\u7159\u82b1\u975a\u4f4d\u63a8\u4ecb|title=\u3010\u8cc0\u6b72\u7159\u82b1\u3011\u521d\u4e8c\u7159\u82b1\u532f\u6f14\u6709\u8c6c\u9f3b\u5716\u6848 \u56db\u500b\u7747\u7159\u82b1\u975a\u4f4d\u63a8\u4ecb|website=\u9999\u6e2f01|language=zh-HK}}</ref>\n\nXu Shiyin released her second solo \"You Are Not Wrong\" ([[Simplified Chinese characters|simplified chinese]] : \u662f\u4f60\u6ca1\u9519\u4e86) in March 14. The song was written by Shiyin and composed by Mikey Jiao. It represented the discovery of her career and thanked the people who supported her.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ent.people.com.cn/n1/2019/0315/c1012-30978468.html|title=\u8bb8\u8bd7\u8335\u53d1\u5e03\u6700\u65b0\u72ec\u7acb\u4f5c\u8bcd\u5355\u66f2\u300a\u662f\u4f60\u6ca1\u9519\u4e86\u300b\u00a0--\u4eba\u6c11\u7f51\u5a31\u4e50\u9891\u9053--\u4eba\u6c11\u7f51|website=ent.people.com.cn}}</ref>  She also released her third song \"Yi Sheng Tian Ya\"([[simplified chinese]]: \u4e00\u751f\u5929\u6daf) on 12 November. \n\nDebbie was invited to participate in the Asian Cultural Carnival on May 15. She performed the song \"A Youthful Asia\" with [[William Chan]], [[Lay Zhang|Zhang Yixing]], and Young Asia Group. SING performed the songs \"Ru Meng Ling\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u5982\u68a6\u4ee4) and \"Bu Xian\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u4e0d\u7fa1) on Yo!Bang on May 26.\n\nBian Li released her first solo \"Someday\" ([[Pinyin]]: Mou Yi Tian)([[simplified chinese]]: \u67d0\u4e00\u5929) on July 5. Later, on November 4, she released her second song \"Deng\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u7b49).\n\nOn March 17, SING performed at the One Yeah Pop Up+ Festival held in [[Xi'an]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sohu.com/a/300872156_729517|title=2019\u73a9\u91ce\u6f6e\u9752\u5e74\u6587\u5316\u8282\uff08\u897f\u5b89\u7ad9\uff09\u76db\u5927\u97f3\u4e50\u8282\u9080\u4f60\u6765\uff01_\u8bf4\u5531|website=www.sohu.com}}</ref> SING then performed the songs \"Guo Chao Shi Dai\" ([[Simplified Chinese characters|Simplified chinese]]: \u56fd\u6f6e\u65f6\u4ee3) and \"Chuan Ren\" ([[simplified chinese]]: \u4f20\u4eba) in another edition of the same festival on May 11.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinanews.com/cul/2019/05-11/8833660.shtml|title=\"\u6709\u95f4\u56fd\u6f6e\u9986\"\u8bb2\u8ff0\u4e2d\u56fd\u98ce \u4e3b\u9898\u66f2\u7531SING\u5973\u56e2\u6f14\u5531-\u4e2d\u65b0\u7f51|website=www.chinanews.com}}</ref> \n\nOn August 8, SING released their Chinese Style Electronic Music digital album ''Jie Meng''. The album includes three songs, which are \"Jie Meng\", \"Shao Nian Zhong Guo\" and \"Pi Pa Xing\". SING celebrated their 4th anniversary since debut and also released the song \"Hua Qiang\" ([[Simplified Chinese]]: \u82b1\u67aa) on October 25 in Beijing, China. On November 17, SING was announced as the winner of the Rising Popularity Group of the Year award and also performed the song \"Hua Qiang\" ([[Simplified Chinese]]: \u82b1\u67aa) at the Asia Music Festival 2019 in Shenzhen, China.\n\n==Members==\n===Current===\n*Qin Yu (\u79e6\u745c) (Sophie)\n*Bian Li (\u8fb9\u4e3d) (Jessica)\n*Lin Hui (\u6797\u6167) (Haha)\n*Jiang Shen (\u848b\u7533) (Debbie)\n*Xu Shiyin (\u8bb8\u8bd7\u8335) (Valentina)\n*Chen Li (\u9648\u4e3d) (Pink)\n*Wu Yao (\u5434\u7476) (Miko)\n*[[Lai Meiyun]] (\u8d56\u7f8e\u4e91) (Sunny) (currently active in [[Rocket Girls 101]])\n\n===Former===\n*Lin Jinyi (\u6797\u6d25\u4f0a) (Magical)\n*Cai Sha (\u8521\u838e) (SaSa)\n*Wang Wenjie (\u738b\u6587\u6d01) (Candy)\n*Chen Wenrou (\u9648\u6e29\u67d4) (Ruby)\n*Gong Tianying (\u9f9a\u5929\u9896) (Lorinda)\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"1\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"1\" | Album details\n|-\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''SING'' (SING\u540c\u540d\u4e13\u8f91)\n|\n*Released: December 29, 2017\n*Label: JSJ International Entertainment\n*Formats: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[Music download|digital download]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Jie Meng'' (\u89e3\u68a6)\n|\n*Released: August 10, 2019\n*Formats: digital download\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\" | Peak chart <br> positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" | Album\n|-\n! <small>[[Billboard China|CHN]]</small><br><ref name=\"gaon_digital_chart\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboardchina.cn/top/top100/|title=Billboard China Top 100|publisher=Billboard China}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Qing Chun De Gao Bai\" ([[Simplified Chinese characters|simplified chinese]]: \u9752\u6625\u7684\u544a\u767d)\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2015\