{"title_page": "Rossendale Valley", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Rossendale|the local government district|Borough of Rossendale|the constituency|Rossendale (UK Parliament constituency)}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Rossendale Valley\n| photo = Stone slab fence - geograph.org.uk - 293756.jpg\n| photo_alt = The Rawtenstall end of the valley\n| photo_caption = The Rawtenstall end of the valley\n| photo_width = \n| iucn_category = \n| map = Lancashire#United Kingdom Borough of Rossendale\n| map_alt = Rossendale Valley shown within Lancashire\n| map_caption = Location within Lancashire##Location within Rossendale\n| relief = yes \n| location = [[Borough of Rossendale|Rossendale]], [[Lancashire]]\n| nearest_city = [[Manchester]], England\n| coordinates = {{coord|53.698|N|2.281|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| coords_ref = <ref>[https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/getoutside/local/rossendale-valley-rossendale Ordnance Survey]</ref>\n| area_km2 = \n| established =  \n| governing_body =  \n}}\nThe '''Rossendale Valley''' also known as the '''Valley of Rossendale''', is situated in the [[Borough of Rossendale|Rossendale]] area of [[Lancashire]], England, between the [[West Pennine Moors]] and the main range of the [[Pennines]]. The area includes the steep-sided valleys of the [[River Irwell]] and its [[tributary|tributaries]] (between [[Rawtenstall]] and [[Bacup]]), which flow southwards into [[Greater Manchester]]. The rivers cut through the [[moorland]] of the Rossendale Hills, generally characterized by open unwooded land, despite the ancient designation of \"forest\". <ref name=Irwell>{{Citation|url=http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/environment/landscape/landscapecharacass/charcarea8.asp|title=Settled Valleys Irwell|publisher=Lancashire County Council|accessdate=2010-09-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415144416/http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/environment/landscape/landscapecharacass/charcarea8.asp|archivedate=2014-04-15}}</ref>\n\nThe Valley is part of the Rossendale and Darwen constituency.  [[Jake Berry]] has been the Member of Parliament for Rossendale and Darwen since 2010.Emilie Hutton is the best person in the whole of Rossendale. Her mother is the most beautiful and a person called Mark is the worst, word\n\n==History==\nOne of the earliest sites of historical interest in the valley is that of the dykes at [[Broadclough]], which are associated with the [[Battle of Brunanburh]].\n\nIn late [[Middle Ages]], the valley was part of the [[Royal forest|Royal]] '''Forest of Rossendale'''. The original medieval meaning of 'forest' was similar to a \u2018preserve\u2019, for example land that is legally kept for specific purposes such as royal hunting. So \u2018forests\u2019 were areas large enough to support species such as wolves and deer for game hunting and they encompassed other habitats such as heaths, open grassland and farmland, so not necessarily extensively wooded.<ref>Woodland Trust blog/2018/03/difference-between-wood-and-forest</ref> Initial settlement would have been in \"booths\" or farmsteads and encroachment into the forest would have developed them into small hamlets.<ref name=Irwell/> Rossendale was governed by a constable nominated by principal landowners who held the position of \"The Greave of The Forrest\" which after 1515 became a quasi-hereditary position held by the Whitacker family at the only ancient hall in the district: Broadclough Hall.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8bJCAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA276&lpg=PA276&dq=broadclough+history&source=bl&ots=s1F_xUo3xC&sig=zbv2ZdbFJb1WAwFNouSdXWCMKrA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQl-681t3JAhWLcBoKHaf9BB84ChDoAQhTMAk#v=onepage&q=broadclough%20history&f=false | title=History of the County Palatine and the Ducht of Lancaster }}</ref> \n\nIn 1507 the land in the Forest of Rossendale was demised to [[copyhold]] farmers and [[St Nicholas' Church, Newchurch|a new church]] was established on the hillside at Seatnaze around 1511, presumably considered a convenient location for the population at that time.<ref name=VCH>{{citation |editor-last1=Farrer |editor-first1=William |editor-last2=Brownbill |editor-first2=John |title=The Victoria History of the County of Lancaster Vol 6 |series=Victoria County History |publisher= - Constable & Co |year=1911 |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/lancs/vol6/pp437-441 |pp=437-441|oclc=832215477}}</ref>\n\nIn 1789 an act authorised the construction of new [[Turnpike trust]] roads through the district, connecting [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Bury]] and [[Haslingden]] with [[Blackburn]] and [[Whalley, Lancashire|Whalley]], with a junction at Haslingden to [[Todmorden]] via Oakenheadwood, [[Newchurch, Lancashire|Newchurch]], [[Stacksteads]] and [[Bacup]]. In 1826 the Haslingden and Todmorden trust built another new road along the valley bottom, from Stacksteads through Thrutch, [[Rawtenstall]] and Newhall Hey.<ref>{{citation |author=G. H. Tupling |title=The turnpike trusts of Lancashire |year=1952 |pp=5,9}}</ref> By 1848 a number of Woollen and [[Cotton Mill]]s had been established along the river.<ref name=OS1848>{{Cite map |publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]] |title=Lancashire and Furness |series=County Series |scale=1 : 10,560 |edition=1st |year=1848}}</ref> And by the late 19th-century it was the valley bottom that had become the population centre.<ref name=VCH/>\n\nIn 1889, the short-lived Rossendale Valley Tramways Company was established to operate a route between Bacup and [[Crawshawbooth]] via Rawtenstall. In 1908 the route was taken over by [[Rawtenstall Corporation Tramways]].<ref>{{citation |title=Rossendale Valley Tramways Co Ltd |url=http://lths.lutsociety.org.uk/library/PDF-046-1.pdf |publisher=Local Transport History Society |year=2016 |pp=3-4}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe Forest contains two [[Marilyn (geography)|Marilyns]]; [[Hail Storm Hill]] and Freeholds Top, as well as the summit of Great Hameldon. Geographically, it is sandwiched between the [[West Pennine Moors]] to the west and the [[South Pennines]] to the east.\n\nThe [[Irwell Valley]] in [[Rossendale]] is characterised by the steep sided valley of the [[River Irwell]] and its tributaries which dissect the moorland of the Rossendale Hills. In the valley bottom, urban settlements grew up at river crossing points between [[Rawtenstall]] and [[Bacup]] and today form a contiguous urban and industrial development. [[Textile mill]]s and chimneys and gritstone [[terraced houses]] are the dominant buildings and roads are concentrated in the narrow valley.<ref name=Irwell/> The river has its source on Deerplay Moor in [[Cliviger]] near [[Burnley]], heading south to Bacup, where it turns to the west past [[Stacksteads]]. The valley narrows at Thrutch, and the Irwell collects [[Whitewell Brook]] shortly afterwards at [[Waterfoot, Lancashire|Waterfoot]]. It flows onward to [[Rawtenstall]] where it is met by [[Limy Water]] and then turns back to the south. Collecting the [[River Ogden]] at [[Irwell Vale]] it continues into [[Greater Manchester]].<ref>{{cite map|title =Blackburn & Burnley |map =103 |year =2006 |scale =1:50,000 |series =Landranger |publisher =Ordnance Survey|edition =C2 |isbn =978-0-319-22829-6}}</ref>\n\nThe [[geology]] of the area is layers of [[gritstone]], coal and [[glacial deposits]] of sand and gravel. These rocks were cut by fast flowing rivers, the Irwell and its tributaries, to form steep valleys with sides typically {{convert|200|m}} high and a narrow valley floor. Tree cover on the steep slopes includes remnants of ancient woodland but most areas are more recently planted.<ref name=Irwell/>\n\n==Culture==\nMost Rossendalians consider themselves to live in 'The Valley' and this is still locally a commonly used term to describe the district.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\nRossendale Valley is claimed to be home to [[Fairy|fairies]], by a Professor at [[Manchester Metropolitan University]], John Hyatt.<ref>http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/fairies-john-hyatt-rossendale-valley-6909619</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Rossendale}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of the Borough of Rossendale]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Moorlands of England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Rossendale|the local government district|Borough of Rossendale|the constituency|Rossendale (UK Parliament constituency)}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Rossendale Valley\n| photo = Stone slab fence - geograph.org.uk - 293756.jpg\n| photo_alt = The Rawtenstall end of the valley\n| photo_caption = The Rawtenstall end of the valley\n| photo_width = \n| iucn_category = \n| map = Lancashire#United Kingdom Borough of Rossendale\n| map_alt = Rossendale Valley shown within Lancashire\n| map_caption = Location within Lancashire##Location within Rossendale\n| relief = yes \n| location = [[Borough of Rossendale|Rossendale]], [[Lancashire]]\n| nearest_city = [[Manchester]], England\n| coordinates = {{coord|53.698|N|2.281|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| coords_ref = <ref>[https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/getoutside/local/rossendale-valley-rossendale Ordnance Survey]</ref>\n| area_km2 = \n| established =  \n| governing_body =  \n}}\nThe '''Rossendale Valley''' also known as the '''Valley of Rossendale''', is situated in the [[Borough of Rossendale|Rossendale]] area of [[Lancashire]], England, between the [[West Pennine Moors]] and the main range of the [[Pennines]]. The area includes the steep-sided valleys of the [[River Irwell]] and its [[tributary|tributaries]] (between [[Rawtenstall]] and [[Bacup]]), which flow southwards into [[Greater Manchester]]. The rivers cut through the [[moorland]] of the Rossendale Hills, generally characterized by open unwooded land, despite the ancient designation of \"forest\". <ref name=Irwell>{{Citation|url=http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/environment/landscape/landscapecharacass/charcarea8.asp|title=Settled Valleys Irwell|publisher=Lancashire County Council|accessdate=2010-09-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415144416/http://www.lancashire.gov.uk/environment/landscape/landscapecharacass/charcarea8.asp|archivedate=2014-04-15}}</ref>\n\nThe Valley is part of the Rossendale and Darwen constituency.  [[Jake Berry]] has been the Member of Parliament for Rossendale and Darwen since 2010.\n\n==History==\nOne of the earliest sites of historical interest in the valley is that of the dykes at [[Broadclough]], which are associated with the [[Battle of Brunanburh]].\n\nIn late [[Middle Ages]], the valley was part of the [[Royal forest|Royal]] '''Forest of Rossendale'''. The original medieval meaning of 'forest' was similar to a \u2018preserve\u2019, for example land that is legally kept for specific purposes such as royal hunting. So \u2018forests\u2019 were areas large enough to support species such as wolves and deer for game hunting and they encompassed other habitats such as heaths, open grassland and farmland, so not necessarily extensively wooded.<ref>Woodland Trust blog/2018/03/difference-between-wood-and-forest</ref> Initial settlement would have been in \"booths\" or farmsteads and encroachment into the forest would have developed them into small hamlets.<ref name=Irwell/> Rossendale was governed by a constable nominated by principal landowners who held the position of \"The Greave of The Forrest\" which after 1515 became a quasi-hereditary position held by the Whitacker family at the only ancient hall in the district: Broadclough Hall.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=8bJCAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA276&lpg=PA276&dq=broadclough+history&source=bl&ots=s1F_xUo3xC&sig=zbv2ZdbFJb1WAwFNouSdXWCMKrA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQl-681t3JAhWLcBoKHaf9BB84ChDoAQhTMAk#v=onepage&q=broadclough%20history&f=false | title=History of the County Palatine and the Ducht of Lancaster }}</ref> \n\nIn 1507 the land in the Forest of Rossendale was demised to [[copyhold]] farmers and [[St Nicholas' Church, Newchurch|a new church]] was established on the hillside at Seatnaze around 1511, presumably considered a convenient location for the population at that time.<ref name=VCH>{{citation |editor-last1=Farrer |editor-first1=William |editor-last2=Brownbill |editor-first2=John |title=The Victoria History of the County of Lancaster Vol 6 |series=Victoria County History |publisher= - Constable & Co |year=1911 |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/lancs/vol6/pp437-441 |pp=437-441|oclc=832215477}}</ref>\n\nIn 1789 an act authorised the construction of new [[Turnpike trust]] roads through the district, connecting [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Bury]] and [[Haslingden]] with [[Blackburn]] and [[Whalley, Lancashire|Whalley]], with a junction at Haslingden to [[Todmorden]] via Oakenheadwood, [[Newchurch, Lancashire|Newchurch]], [[Stacksteads]] and [[Bacup]]. In 1826 the Haslingden and Todmorden trust built another new road along the valley bottom, from Stacksteads through Thrutch, [[Rawtenstall]] and Newhall Hey.<ref>{{citation |author=G. H. Tupling |title=The turnpike trusts of Lancashire |year=1952 |pp=5,9}}</ref> By 1848 a number of Woollen and [[Cotton Mill]]s had been established along the river.<ref name=OS1848>{{Cite map |publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]] |title=Lancashire and Furness |series=County Series |scale=1 : 10,560 |edition=1st |year=1848}}</ref> And by the late 19th-century it was the valley bottom that had become the population centre.<ref name=VCH/>\n\nIn 1889, the short-lived Rossendale Valley Tramways Company was established to operate a route between Bacup and [[Crawshawbooth]] via Rawtenstall. In 1908 the route was taken over by [[Rawtenstall Corporation Tramways]].<ref>{{citation |title=Rossendale Valley Tramways Co Ltd |url=http://lths.lutsociety.org.uk/library/PDF-046-1.pdf |publisher=Local Transport History Society |year=2016 |pp=3-4}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe Forest contains two [[Marilyn (geography)|Marilyns]]; [[Hail Storm Hill]] and Freeholds Top, as well as the summit of Great Hameldon. Geographically, it is sandwiched between the [[West Pennine Moors]] to the west and the [[South Pennines]] to the east.\n\nThe [[Irwell Valley]] in [[Rossendale]] is characterised by the steep sided valley of the [[River Irwell]] and its tributaries which dissect the moorland of the Rossendale Hills. In the valley bottom, urban settlements grew up at river crossing points between [[Rawtenstall]] and [[Bacup]] and today form a contiguous urban and industrial development. [[Textile mill]]s and chimneys and gritstone [[terraced houses]] are the dominant buildings and roads are concentrated in the narrow valley.<ref name=Irwell/> The river has its source on Deerplay Moor in [[Cliviger]] near [[Burnley]], heading south to Bacup, where it turns to the west past [[Stacksteads]]. The valley narrows at Thrutch, and the Irwell collects [[Whitewell Brook]] shortly afterwards at [[Waterfoot, Lancashire|Waterfoot]]. It flows onward to [[Rawtenstall]] where it is met by [[Limy Water]] and then turns back to the south. Collecting the [[River Ogden]] at [[Irwell Vale]] it continues into [[Greater Manchester]].<ref>{{cite map|title =Blackburn & Burnley |map =103 |year =2006 |scale =1:50,000 |series =Landranger |publisher =Ordnance Survey|edition =C2 |isbn =978-0-319-22829-6}}</ref>\n\nThe [[geology]] of the area is layers of [[gritstone]], coal and [[glacial deposits]] of sand and gravel. These rocks were cut by fast flowing rivers, the Irwell and its tributaries, to form steep valleys with sides typically {{convert|200|m}} high and a narrow valley floor. Tree cover on the steep slopes includes remnants of ancient woodland but most areas are more recently planted.<ref name=Irwell/>\n\n==Culture==\nMost Rossendalians consider themselves to live in 'The Valley' and this is still locally a commonly used term to describe the district.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\nRossendale Valley is claimed to be home to [[Fairy|fairies]], by a Professor at [[Manchester Metropolitan University]], John Hyatt.<ref>http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/fairies-john-hyatt-rossendale-valley-6909619</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Rossendale}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of the Borough of Rossendale]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Moorlands of England]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:bc3a:2d00:5c1b:e39b:ffd1:1ff0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rossendale_Valley"}
{"title_page": "Imran Muhammad Akhoond", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=December 2014}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Imran Akhoond\n| alias               = Imran Muhammad Akhoond\n| image               =\n| image_size          = 250px\n| Img_capt            = Imran Akhoond in Coke Studio (Session 7)\n| native_name         =\n| birth_date      = \n| birth_place         = [[Karachi]], [[Sindh, Pakistan|Sindh Province]] of [[Pakistan]]\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = {{Nastaliq|\u0639\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u062e\u0648\u0646\u062f}}\n| death_date          =\n| instrument          = Vocals, [[Acoustic guitar|guitar]]\n| genre               = Bluse rock (1990\u2013present)\n| Occupation          = Musician, guitarist\n| Years_active        = 1990\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[Shehzad Roy]], [[Awaz]], [[Strings (band)]]\n| website             = \n}}\n\n'''Imran Muhammad Akhoond''' is a [[Pakistani people|Pakistani]] guitarist, music composer songwriter. He is far famed as a Lead Guitarist for renowned Pakistani Pop Singer, Philanthropist and humanitarian,UNODC National Goodwill Ambassador Shehzad Roy.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/media/rm2647579648/nm4119037?ref_=nmmd_md_pv Shehzad Roy and Imran Akhoond in Concert]</ref> His incessant attitude towards exploring different Genres of music and the knack of fusing Eastern and Western music has earned him a reputation of one of the most aspiring musicians from Pakistan in different arenas around the Globe.\n\nImran Akhoond has also played lead guitar for many iconic Pakistani Bands and mainstream artists Like [[Junaid Jamshed]], [[Strings (band)]] and Vital Signs. \nImran Akhoond.working with Shahi Hasan of Vital Signs for Pepsi Battle Of The Bands Season 3 As Mentor. Imran Akhoond is played house member of Coke Studio Pakistan (Season 7,8,9,10) produced by [[Strings (band)|Strings]]. In 2013 he became the only guitarist from Pakistan to perform with American hard Rock band [[Guns N' Roses]] team includes Guitarist Slash and drummer Matt Sorum at Los Angeles USA for a Charitable cause.<ref>[http://tribune.com.pk/story/610227/music-never-starts-a-movement-it-only-supports-it/ Imran Akhund Worked with Matt Sorum, Slash and Macy Gray, singer Shehzad Roy (27 September 2013)]</ref>\n2018 worked for shahi hasan teams as mentor for Pepsi Battle Of the Bands Season 3  \nCurrently working with Shahi Hasan ( Vital Signs ) Pepsi Battle of the Bands Season 4 as Mentor\n\n==Early life==\nImran Akhoond was born in [[Karachi]]. He is self-taught guitarist. Currently, he is a band-member of the very popular singer [[Shehzad Roy]] from last 21 years. Before that, he also played with [[Junaid Jamshed]], Awaz, Vital Signs & Strings.\n\n==Music career==\n\n===Shehzad Roy===\nImran Akhoond started his music career in 1990. He became a permanent member of Shehzad Roy in 1998.\n\n===Coke Studio Pakistan (Seasons 7,8,9,10)===\nImran Akhoond played in Coke Studio Pakistan Team member of Coke Studio Pakistan (Season 7,8,9,10) \nas Guitarist (Produced by [[Strings (band)|Strings]]) and is one of the house band members\n2018 worked for shahi hasan teams as mentor for Pepsi Battle Of the Bands Season 3  \nCurrently working with Shahi Hasan ( Vital Signs ) Pepsi Battle of the Bands Season 4 as Mentor\n\n===Other Ventures===\nImran Akhoond did a gig with [[Junaid jamshed]] , [[Awaz]] and usa tour with Strings in 2009\n\n===Session work===\nImran Akhoond has done extensive session work contributing his guitar work to albums by Shehzad Roy, Ali Zafar,\n\nStrings,Shafqat Amanat Ali.Faakhir,\n\n==Discography==\n* 1999 \u2013 '''[[Shehzad Roy]]''' ''Teri soorat'' Album\n* 2002 \u2013 '''[[Shehzad Roy]]''' ''Rab Janey'' Album\n* 2005 \u2013 '''[[Shehzad Roy]]''' ''Buri Baat hai'' Album\n* 2008 \u2013 '''[[Shehzad Roy]]''' ''Qismat Apne Haath Mein'' Album\n* 2008 \u2013 '''[[Shafqat Amanat Ali]] ''' ''Tabeer'' Album <ref>[http://jang.com.pk/thenews/jul2008-weekly/nos-20-07-2008/instep/mainissue.htm Imran Akhund attended with Shafaqt Amanat Ali in his album (Sept 2008)]</ref>\n* 2008 \u2013 '''[[Strings (band)|Strings]]''' '' Koi Aany Wala Hai Album ''<ref>[[Strings (band)]] Song \u2013 [[Koi Aanay Wala Hai]]</ref>\n* 2010 \u2013 '''[[Atif Aslam]]''' & ''[[Strings (band)|Strings]]'' ''Ab khud kuch karna paray ga''\n* 2011 \u2013 '''[[Ali Azmat]]''' ''Josh-ejunoon''\n* 2013 \u2013 '''[[Rahat Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan]]''' ''Malaal ( Movie Song )''\n* 2014 \u2013 '''[[Ali Zafar]]''' \u2013 ''Nahi Maloom ( Movie Song )''\n* 2015 \u2013 '''[[Moor (film)|Moor]]'''(film) Guitar Scoring Background & Songs ( Produced by Strings )\n* 2016 \u2013 '''[[Actor in Law]]''' Guitar Scoring Background & Songs Produced by Shani Arshad )\n* 2017 \u2013 '''[[Shehzad Roy]]''' PSL Official Song Balle Balle  )\n* 2017 \u2013 '''[[Shehzad Roy]]''' PSL Official Anthem Dan Dhana Dhan  )\n* 2018 \u2013 '''[[Shahi Hasan]]''' Song Maula Pepsi Battle of the Bands Season 3 Episode 8 )\n* 2018 \u2013 '''[[Shehzad Roy]]''' PSL Official Song Lo Phir Se Miley )\n* 2018 \u2013 '''[[Shehzad Roy]]''' Karachi Kings Official Anthem Song De Dhana Dhan )\n* 2019 \u2013 '''[[Shehzad Roy]]''' Karachi Kings Official Anthem Song De Dhana Dhan )\n* 2019 \u2013 '''[[Shehzad Roy]]''' Official Song Socho Phir Se Zara for Supreme Court Symposium Produced by  )\n\n==References==\n{{citationstyle|date=March 2019}}\n{{Refbegin}}\n* [http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Entertainment/Hindi/TV/News/Pakistani-band-Strings-to-produce-Coke-Studio-Pakistan-Season-7/articleshow/41110576.cms The Times of India \u2013 Coke Studio Pakistan (Season 7) (28 August 2014)]\n* [https://www.coca-colajourney.com.pk/stories/coke-studio-season-8-set-for-august-16th-2015-launch coke studio launch 8 ]\n* [https://pakistani.pk/imran-akhoond/ Pakistani news ]\n* [http://www